[2026-03-21 11:34:11] [pre-recon] [LLM] Turn 4: {"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014jaRxC7yaVf9v7pFki2vFS","name":"Task","input":{"description":"Architecture Scanner Agent","subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt":"You are an Architecture Scanner Agent performing security-focused code analysis. Your job is to map the application's structure, technology stack, and critical components.\n\n**TASKS:**\n1. Start by examining the root directory structure (list files and directories)\n2. Identify the primary language(s) and framework(s) used\n3. Read dependency manifests (package.json, go.mod, requirements.txt, Gemfile, pom.xml, build.gradle, Cargo.toml, etc.)\n4. Identify the architectural pattern (monolith, microservices, serverless, etc.)\n5. Find configuration files (docker-compose.yml, Dockerfile, nginx.conf, kubernetes configs, .env files, config directories)\n6. Identify security-relevant middleware, frameworks, and libraries\n7. Map trust boundaries between components\n8. Identify infrastructure configurations (reverse proxies, load balancers, CDN configs)\n9. Look for security headers configuration (HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options, etc.)\n10. Identify build and deployment tooling\n\n**OUTPUT FORMAT:**\nProvide a detailed report covering:\n- **Technology Stack:** Languages, frameworks, versions, and their security implications\n- **Architectural Pattern:** How the app is structured and trust boundaries\n- **Configuration Files:** All config files found with security relevance\n- **Infrastructure:** Deployment configs, reverse proxies, container configs\n- **Security Headers:** Where and how security headers are configured\n- **Dependency Analysis:** Notable dependencies with security implications\n- **Build/Deploy Pipeline:** CI/CD and deployment tooling\n\nBe thorough and provide exact file paths for everything you find. Focus on security implications of each finding.","max_turns":30},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}
