[2026-03-21 11:58:57] [pre-recon] [LLM] Turn 257: {"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WEuyjj1fhiLPRPtav9opmh","name":"Task","input":{"description":"SSRF/External Request Tracer","subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt":"You are an SSRF/External Request Tracer Agent performing security-focused code analysis on a Next.js e-commerce frontend application located at `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web`.\n\n**APPLICATION CONTEXT:** This is a Next.js 14 App Router frontend for an e-commerce site. It has several API proxy routes that make server-side requests:\n- `/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts` - Avatar image proxy (SSRF candidate)\n- `/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts` - Strapi image proxy (SSRF candidate)\n- `/api/stripe/config/route.ts` - Stripe config endpoint\n- `/api/analyze-product/route.ts` - Product analysis endpoint\n- Server-side rendering with `server-api.ts` making fetch calls\n- Next.js image optimization configured with wildcard hostname `**`\n\n**YOUR TASKS:**\n\n1. **Analyze ALL server-side fetch/request calls** in API routes with exact file paths and line numbers\n2. **Trace user input flow** to each server-side request - how does user-controlled data reach the URL/headers/body?\n3. **Analyze the avatar proxy** (`/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts`) in detail:\n   - How are path segments used to construct the upstream URL?\n   - Is there any URL validation or allowlisting?\n   - Can an attacker control the destination host/port/protocol?\n   - Can path traversal reach internal services?\n4. **Analyze the Strapi image proxy** (`/src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts`) in detail:\n   - Same questions as avatar proxy\n   - Note the Strapi API query with user-controlled search terms\n5. **Analyze the product analysis endpoint** (`/src/app/api/analyze-product/route.ts`):\n   - Does it make outbound requests based on user input?\n6. **Find ALL fetch(), axios, http.get, http.request calls** that are server-side\n7. **Check server-side rendering** - do any server components fetch URLs based on user input?\n8. **Check Next.js image optimization** - can the wildcard hostname config be exploited?\n9. **Find ALL redirect handlers** - any open redirect vulnerabilities\n10. **Check for DNS rebinding potential** in URL validation\n11. **Look for internal service URLs** that might be targetable via SSRF (cloud metadata, internal APIs)\n12. **Check if fetch follows redirects** - can SSRF bypass hostname checks via redirect chains?\n\n**For each SSRF sink found, provide:**\n- Exact file path and line number(s)\n- The code constructing the outbound request\n- What user-controlled data influences the request\n- The entry point (API route URL) an attacker would target\n- Protocol/host/port/path control assessment\n- Potential impact (internal network scanning, cloud metadata access, etc.)\n- Risk assessment (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW)\n\nBe extremely thorough and trace every data flow path.","max_turns":30},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}
