[2026-03-21 12:06:43] [pre-recon] [LLM] Turn 387: {"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Sk2SPaVrm3Rsb7o6ELi3pg","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/ssrf_analysis.json","content":"{\n  \"vulnerabilities\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-001\",\n      \"title\": \"Avatar Proxy - Full SSRF via User-Controlled Path Segments (Supabase Branch)\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"13-46\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/avatar/[...path]\",\n      \"description\": \"The avatar proxy route accepts arbitrary path segments from the URL, joins them with '/', and appends them to the SUPABASE_PUBLIC_URL base. When SUPABASE_PUBLIC_URL is configured, the proxy constructs multiple candidate URLs and performs server-side HEAD requests to each. The path segments are entirely user-controlled with NO validation, NO allowlisting, and NO URL sanitization. An attacker can inject path traversal sequences (../) or craft path segments to target arbitrary endpoints on the Supabase host. The fallback candidate at line 31 (`${supabasePublic}/${imagePath}`) directly appends the raw user path, allowing full path control on the Supabase origin. If the HEAD request succeeds (200 OK), the server returns a 307 redirect to that URL (line 39), which could be used as an open redirect to any path on the Supabase origin.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"URL path segments: /api/avatar/ANYTHING/HERE/ATTACKER/CONTROLS -> joined as 'ANYTHING/HERE/ATTACKER/CONTROLS'\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"const imagePath = path.join('/');\\n// ...\\nconst candidates = [\\n  `${supabasePublic}/uploads/users/${imagePath}`,\\n  `${supabasePublic}/images/${imagePath}`,\\n  `${supabasePublic}/users/${imagePath}`,\\n  `${supabasePublic}/${imagePath}`,  // <-- Full path control on Supabase host\\n];\\nfor (const url of candidates) {\\n  const head = await fetch(url, { method: 'HEAD' });\\n  if (head.ok) {\\n    const res = NextResponse.redirect(url, 307); // Open redirect to Supabase path\\n    return res;\\n  }\\n}\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"NO - protocol is inherited from SUPABASE_PUBLIC_URL env var (https)\",\n      \"host_control\": \"NO - host is fixed to Supabase origin (unless env var is manipulated)\",\n      \"port_control\": \"NO - port is inherited from Supabase URL\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL - attacker controls the entire path appended to the base URL\",\n      \"impact\": \"Path traversal on Supabase host; server-side HEAD requests to arbitrary Supabase API endpoints; potential access to Supabase internal storage paths, admin endpoints, or PostgREST API; open redirect via 307 to any valid Supabase path\",\n      \"exploit_example\": \"GET /api/avatar/../../../rest/v1/users?select=* -> HEAD to https://supabase-host.co/rest/v1/users?select=*\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Validate that path segments contain only alphanumeric characters, hyphens, underscores, and dots. Reject segments containing '..' or starting with '/'. Ensure the final resolved URL stays within the expected uploads directory.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-002\",\n      \"title\": \"Avatar Proxy - Full SSRF via User-Controlled Path Segments (Backend Fallback Branch)\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"49-61\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/avatar/[...path]\",\n      \"description\": \"When the Supabase branch fails or is not configured, the proxy falls back to fetching from the backend API server. The user-controlled imagePath is appended to `${serverUrl}/uploads/users/` and a full GET request (not just HEAD) is issued. The response body is then proxied back to the client. This is a classic SSRF: the server fetches arbitrary content from a path the user controls on the backend server. The fetch uses `redirect: 'follow'` (line 60), meaning if the backend returns a redirect, the server will follow it to any destination, potentially bypassing the intended host restriction. An attacker can use path traversal (../) to escape the /uploads/users/ prefix and reach any endpoint on the backend server (e.g., /api/admin, /api/users). The response content is returned to the attacker (line 81-92), making this a 'full read' SSRF.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"URL path segments: /api/avatar/../../api/admin/settings -> fetches serverUrl/uploads/users/../../api/admin/settings -> resolves to serverUrl/api/admin/settings\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"const apiUrl = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL || 'https://kamri-server-production.up.railway.app';\\nconst serverUrl = apiUrl.replace(/\\\\/api$/, '');\\nconst imageUrl = `${serverUrl}/uploads/users/${imagePath}`;\\nconst response = await fetch(imageUrl, {\\n  headers: { 'User-Agent': 'KamriHub-Web/1.0' },\\n  redirect: 'follow', // Follows redirects!\\n});\\n// Response body is proxied back to attacker:\\nconst imageBuffer = await response.arrayBuffer();\\nreturn new NextResponse(imageBuffer, { ... });\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"NO - fixed by NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL\",\n      \"host_control\": \"NO - fixed to backend server host\",\n      \"port_control\": \"NO - fixed to backend server port\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL - path traversal via ../ can escape /uploads/users/ prefix\",\n      \"impact\": \"Full read SSRF on backend server. Attacker can read any endpoint response from the backend server, including admin APIs, user data, internal settings. Combined with redirect: 'follow', if the backend issues a redirect (e.g., to cloud metadata), the server will follow it.\",\n      \"exploit_example\": \"GET /api/avatar/..%2F..%2Fapi%2Fusers%2Fprofile -> fetches backend/uploads/users/../../api/users/profile -> backend/api/users/profile\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Validate path segments: reject '..' and any URL-encoded variants. Allowlist characters to [a-zA-Z0-9._-]. Set redirect: 'error' or 'manual' instead of 'follow'. Add response Content-Type validation to ensure only image types are returned.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-003\",\n      \"title\": \"Strapi Image Proxy - Full SSRF with Multiple Attack Vectors\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"13-172\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/strapi-image/[...path]?id=OPTIONAL\",\n      \"description\": \"The Strapi image proxy has multiple SSRF vectors. Vector 1 (lines 117-128): The user-controlled path segments are directly appended to the Strapi base URL and fetched with GET + redirect:follow. No path validation exists. Vector 2 (lines 33-114): When an 'id' query parameter is provided, the proxy fetches file metadata from Strapi API, then follows the 'url' field from the Strapi response. If the url starts with 'http', it is fetched as an absolute URL (line 59), meaning a compromised/malicious Strapi instance could redirect the proxy to ANY URL including internal services. Vector 3 (lines 137-185): A filename-based search sends user-controlled search terms to the Strapi API, then follows any URL returned in the response. All vectors use redirect: 'follow' and proxy the full response body back to the attacker.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"Path segments (/api/strapi-image/ANY/PATH) and ?id= query parameter\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"// Vector 1: Direct path control\\nconst imageUrl = `${baseUrl}${imagePath.startsWith('/') ? imagePath : `/${imagePath}`}`;\\nresponse = await fetch(imageUrl, { redirect: 'follow' });\\n\\n// Vector 2: Indirect SSRF via Strapi API response URL\\nconst fileUrl = fileData.url;\\nconst finalUrl = fileUrl.startsWith('http') ? fileUrl : `${baseUrl}${fileUrl}`;\\nresponse = await fetch(finalUrl, { redirect: 'follow' });\\n\\n// Vector 3: Search-based - user controls search term\\nconst apiUrl = `${baseUrl}/api/upload/files?filters[name][$contains]=${encodeURIComponent(searchTerm)}`;\\n// Then follows URL from response\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"Partial - base URL protocol comes from env var, but Strapi response URLs starting with 'http' are used as-is (full protocol control via indirect SSRF)\",\n      \"host_control\": \"Partial via Vector 1 (fixed to Strapi host), FULL via Vector 2 (Strapi response can specify any host)\",\n      \"port_control\": \"Partial via Vector 1, FULL via Vector 2\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL - path traversal possible in Vector 1; arbitrary URL in Vector 2\",\n      \"impact\": \"Full read SSRF. Vector 1 allows path traversal on Strapi host. Vector 2 (indirect) allows fetching from ANY URL if Strapi response includes an absolute URL - this is particularly dangerous if Strapi is compromised or if there's a stored XSS/injection in Strapi that modifies file URLs. Response is proxied to attacker with Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *. Could be used for internal network scanning, cloud metadata access (169.254.169.254), or reading from internal services.\",\n      \"exploit_example\": \"GET /api/strapi-image/../../../admin -> path traversal to Strapi admin\\nGET /api/strapi-image/anything?id=VALID_ID (where Strapi file URL is http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/) -> cloud metadata exfiltration\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Validate path segments (reject '..', allow only [a-zA-Z0-9._-/]). For indirect URLs from Strapi API responses, validate that they are relative paths or belong to the expected Strapi hostname. Set redirect: 'manual' and validate redirect targets. Add Content-Type validation on responses.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-004\",\n      \"title\": \"Next.js Image Optimization Wildcard - Universal Image Proxy\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/next.config.js\",\n      \"lines\": \"18-29\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /_next/image?url=ATTACKER_URL&w=WIDTH&q=QUALITY\",\n      \"description\": \"The Next.js image optimization configuration uses a wildcard hostname pattern ('**') for BOTH http and https protocols. This means the built-in /_next/image endpoint will fetch and proxy images from ANY URL on the internet. An attacker can use this as a universal SSRF proxy by requesting /_next/image?url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/&w=64&q=75. While Next.js image optimization validates that the response looks like an image (by Content-Type), many internal services return responses that can be coerced to pass this check, and the error messages may leak information. Additionally, the server makes the outbound connection regardless of whether the response is a valid image, enabling port scanning and service detection via timing/error analysis.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"The 'url' query parameter in /_next/image?url=ATTACKER_CONTROLLED\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"images: {\\n  remotePatterns: [\\n    {\\n      protocol: 'https',\\n      hostname: '**',  // Matches ANY hostname\\n    },\\n    {\\n      protocol: 'http',\\n      hostname: '**',  // Matches ANY hostname including internal IPs\\n    },\\n  ],\\n}\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"FULL - both http and https are allowed\",\n      \"host_control\": \"FULL - any hostname including internal IPs, localhost, cloud metadata IPs\",\n      \"port_control\": \"FULL - any port (no port restriction in remotePatterns)\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL - any path\",\n      \"impact\": \"Universal server-side request proxy. Can reach internal network services, cloud metadata endpoints (169.254.169.254), localhost services, and any external host. Can be used for port scanning via timing analysis. While response content may be filtered by image validation, the outbound request is still made, and error responses can leak information about internal service availability.\",\n      \"exploit_example\": \"GET /_next/image?url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/&w=64&q=75\\nGET /_next/image?url=http://localhost:3001/api/admin/settings&w=64&q=75\\nGET /_next/image?url=http://10.0.0.1:6379/&w=64&q=75 (Redis port scan)\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Replace the wildcard hostname '**' with specific allowed hostnames. Create an explicit allowlist of trusted image domains (e.g., Supabase storage, Strapi, CDN domains). Example: hostname: '*.supabase.co' and hostname: 'your-strapi-domain.com'.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-005\",\n      \"title\": \"Avatar Proxy Open Redirect via 307 Redirect to Supabase\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"34-41\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/avatar/[...path]\",\n      \"description\": \"When a HEAD request to a Supabase candidate URL succeeds, the proxy returns a 307 redirect to that URL. Since the path is fully user-controlled, an attacker can redirect users to any valid path on the Supabase host. While the redirect is limited to the Supabase origin, this can be abused for phishing if the Supabase instance hosts user-uploaded content or has other exploitable endpoints.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"Path segments control the redirect target URL path\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"for (const url of candidates) {\\n  const head = await fetch(url, { method: 'HEAD' });\\n  if (head.ok) {\\n    const res = NextResponse.redirect(url, 307);\\n    return res;\\n  }\\n}\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"NO\",\n      \"host_control\": \"NO - limited to Supabase origin\",\n      \"port_control\": \"NO\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL\",\n      \"impact\": \"Open redirect to any path on the Supabase host. Could be used for phishing or to access Supabase API endpoints directly.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Validate that the resolved path stays within expected image directories. Do not redirect to user-controlled URLs.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-006\",\n      \"title\": \"Strapi Image Proxy - Indirect SSRF via Strapi API File URL Response\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"58-70\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/strapi-image/[...path]?id=FILE_ID\",\n      \"description\": \"When a file ID is provided, the proxy queries the Strapi API for file metadata. The 'url' field from the Strapi response is then used to construct a fetch URL. If the URL starts with 'http', it is used as an absolute URL (line 59). This creates an indirect SSRF where a compromised Strapi database entry could point to any URL. The proxy will fetch from that URL and return the response body. Combined with Strapi's 'formats' object (lines 78-101), each format's URL is also fetched if the primary URL fails, multiplying the attack surface. This is particularly dangerous because: (1) Strapi content may be editable by admin users, (2) a SQL injection in Strapi could modify file URLs, (3) the fetched content is returned with Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"The ?id= parameter selects which file record to use; the file record's URL field is the fetch target\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"const fileUrl = fileData.url || fileData.attributes?.url;\\nconst finalUrl = fileUrl.startsWith('http')\\n  ? fileUrl  // <-- Absolute URL from Strapi DB, NO validation\\n  : `${baseUrl}${fileUrl.startsWith('/') ? fileUrl : `/${fileUrl}`}`;\\nresponse = await fetch(finalUrl, {\\n  headers: { 'User-Agent': 'KamriHub-Web/1.0' },\\n  redirect: 'follow',\\n});\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"FULL via stored Strapi URL\",\n      \"host_control\": \"FULL via stored Strapi URL\",\n      \"port_control\": \"FULL via stored Strapi URL\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL via stored Strapi URL\",\n      \"impact\": \"If a Strapi file record URL is modified (via Strapi admin, SQL injection, or API vulnerability), the proxy becomes a universal SSRF proxy that can reach any URL including internal services, cloud metadata endpoints, and external services. The response is fully proxied back to the attacker with CORS headers allowing any origin.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Validate that absolute URLs in Strapi responses match the expected Strapi hostname. Reject URLs pointing to private IP ranges, localhost, or cloud metadata addresses. Implement a URL allowlist.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-007\",\n      \"title\": \"Server-Side Product Resolution with User-Controlled Slug in Server Components\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/server-api.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"201-259\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /[locale]/product/[slug] or GET /[locale]/produit/[slug]\",\n      \"description\": \"The getProductBySlugOrIdServer function takes a user-controlled slug from the URL and passes it to multiple backend API endpoints: (1) directly as a path parameter to /products/{slug}, (2) as search keywords by splitting on hyphens. While the base URL is server-configured and not user-controllable, the path segment IS user-controlled and is interpolated directly into the URL. This is a limited SSRF where the attacker controls the path parameter sent to the backend. The backend API endpoint is fixed, so the risk is limited to path parameter injection rather than full URL control. However, if the backend API has path-based routing vulnerabilities, this could be exploited.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"URL slug parameter -> used as path parameter in /products/{slug} and as search query\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"export const getProductBySlugOrIdServer = cache(async (\\n  slugOrId: string,\\n  lang?: 'fr' | 'en'\\n): Promise<Product | null> => {\\n  const productId = extractProductIdFromUrl(slugOrId);\\n  // ...\\n  const resp = await getProductServer(productId, lang, CACHE_OPTIONS);\\n  // Falls back to:\\n  const resp = await getProductServer(slugOrId, lang, CACHE_OPTIONS);\\n  // Which calls: serverFetch(`/products/${slugOrId}`, ...)\\n});\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"NO\",\n      \"host_control\": \"NO\",\n      \"port_control\": \"NO\",\n      \"path_control\": \"Partial - controls the path parameter after /products/\",\n      \"impact\": \"Limited. The slug is used as a path segment in API calls to the fixed backend. Could potentially be used for path traversal on the backend API if it doesn't properly handle encoded slashes or '..' sequences.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Validate slug format before using it in API calls. Ensure it matches expected patterns (alphanumeric + hyphens).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-008\",\n      \"title\": \"Strapi Image Proxy - All Fetch Calls Use redirect: 'follow' Enabling SSRF via Redirect Chain\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"65-69, 89-92, 123-128, 167-172\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/strapi-image/[...path]\",\n      \"description\": \"All four fetch() calls in the Strapi image proxy use `redirect: 'follow'`. This means that even if the initial URL is constrained to the Strapi host, if ANY response in the chain returns a 3xx redirect to an internal URL (like http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/ or http://localhost:6379/), the proxy will follow it. This is a classic redirect-chain SSRF bypass. A specially crafted Strapi endpoint or a Strapi misconfiguration that returns redirects could be exploited to reach internal services.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"Path segments and ?id= parameter determine which URLs are initially fetched\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"response = await fetch(finalUrl, {\\n  headers: { 'User-Agent': 'KamriHub-Web/1.0' },\\n  redirect: 'follow',  // Will follow redirects to ANY destination\\n});\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain (initial request may be https, but redirect can go to http)\",\n      \"host_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain\",\n      \"port_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain\",\n      \"impact\": \"If the Strapi server (or any intermediary) returns a redirect to an internal URL, the proxy will follow it and return the response. This bypasses any hostname-based restrictions. The response body is proxied back with CORS headers.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Use redirect: 'manual' for all fetch calls. Inspect redirect Location headers and validate they point to allowed hosts before following.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-009\",\n      \"title\": \"Avatar Proxy - Fetch Uses redirect: 'follow' Enabling Redirect-Chain SSRF\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"55-61\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/avatar/[...path]\",\n      \"description\": \"The fallback fetch in the avatar proxy uses `redirect: 'follow'` (line 60). The comment on line 59 even states 'Ne pas suivre les redirections automatiquement pour eviter les boucles' (Do not follow redirects automatically to avoid loops), yet the code sets redirect: 'follow' which DOES follow redirects. This inconsistency suggests the developer intended to disable redirect following but implemented the opposite. If the backend returns a redirect to an internal service, the proxy will follow it.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"Path segments control the URL path on the backend server\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"const response = await fetch(imageUrl, {\\n  headers: { 'User-Agent': 'KamriHub-Web/1.0' },\\n  // Ne pas suivre les redirections automatiquement pour eviter les boucles\\n  redirect: 'follow',  // BUG: Comment says don't follow, code says follow!\\n});\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain\",\n      \"host_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain\",\n      \"port_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain\",\n      \"path_control\": \"FULL via redirect chain\",\n      \"impact\": \"Backend could redirect the request to any internal URL. The response is proxied back to the attacker as image content.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Change redirect: 'follow' to redirect: 'manual'. Validate redirect targets before following them.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-010\",\n      \"title\": \"Exposed Secrets in .env File - Supabase Service Role Key and API Keys\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/.env\",\n      \"lines\": \"15-21\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"N/A (configuration exposure, amplifies SSRF impact)\",\n      \"description\": \"The .env file contains the Supabase service_role JWT key, Stripe test publishable key, Google Maps API key, and a Strapi license key. The Supabase service_role key (SUPABASE_KEY) grants admin access to the Supabase database, bypassing Row-Level Security. While this is not an SSRF vulnerability itself, it dramatically amplifies the impact of SSRF vulnerabilities: if an attacker can use SSRF-001 to reach the Supabase REST API, they could use the service_role key from environment variables to perform authenticated requests with full admin privileges. Note: this file is committed to the repository.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"N/A\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"SUPABASE_KEY=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9... (service_role JWT)\\nNEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=pk_test_51SU1...\\nNEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY=AIzaSyCtlI5rM3SYA...\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"N/A\",\n      \"host_control\": \"N/A\",\n      \"port_control\": \"N/A\",\n      \"path_control\": \"N/A\",\n      \"impact\": \"Amplifies SSRF impact. If SSRF reaches Supabase, the service_role key enables full database access. Stripe and Google API keys may enable unauthorized API usage.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Remove secrets from committed .env file. Use .env.example with placeholder values. Rotate all exposed keys immediately. Ensure .env is in .gitignore.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-011\",\n      \"title\": \"DNS Rebinding Potential - No DNS Resolution Pinning in Proxy Routes\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"36, 55\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/avatar/[...path] and GET /api/strapi-image/[...path]\",\n      \"description\": \"Neither the avatar proxy nor the Strapi image proxy implements DNS resolution pinning. While the hostnames are currently derived from environment variables (not directly user-controlled), if any URL validation were added in the future that checks the hostname against an allowlist, an attacker could bypass it using DNS rebinding. The fetch() calls in Node.js do not pin DNS resolution, so a hostname could resolve to a public IP during validation but resolve to an internal IP (e.g., 169.254.169.254 or 127.0.0.1) during the actual fetch. This is a defense-in-depth concern for the current proxy architecture.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"Path segments (currently), potentially hostnames if URL validation is added\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"// No DNS pinning - fetch resolves DNS at connection time\\nconst head = await fetch(url, { method: 'HEAD' });\\n// Between HEAD and the subsequent redirect/fetch, DNS could change\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"N/A\",\n      \"host_control\": \"N/A (currently)\",\n      \"port_control\": \"N/A (currently)\",\n      \"path_control\": \"N/A\",\n      \"impact\": \"If hostname-based URL validation is added in the future without DNS pinning, attackers could bypass it via DNS rebinding to reach internal services.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"When implementing URL validation, resolve hostnames and validate the IP address rather than the hostname. Consider using a library that pins DNS resolution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"SSRF-012\",\n      \"title\": \"Strapi Image Proxy - User-Controlled Search Term Injection into Strapi API Query\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": \"143-184\",\n      \"entry_point\": \"GET /api/strapi-image/[...path]\",\n      \"description\": \"When the direct URL fetch returns 404, the proxy extracts the filename from the path and uses it to search the Strapi API via `filters[name][$contains]=SEARCH_TERM`. While the search term is URL-encoded (line 151), this still allows injection of arbitrary search terms into the Strapi API, potentially returning unexpected file records. Combined with SSRF-006 (following URLs from API responses), this creates a chain: attacker controls search term -> Strapi returns matching file records -> proxy follows the URL from the record. If an attacker can influence what file records exist in Strapi (e.g., by uploading a file with a URL pointing to an internal service), this becomes a full SSRF chain.\",\n      \"user_controlled_data\": \"Path segments -> last segment is extracted as filename -> used as Strapi API search filter\",\n      \"code_snippet\": \"const fileName = imagePath.split('/').pop();\\nconst searchTerms = [\\n  fileName,\\n  fileName.replace(/\\\\.[^.]+$/, ''),\\n];\\nfor (const searchTerm of searchTerms) {\\n  const apiUrl = `${baseUrl}/api/upload/files?filters[name][$contains]=${encodeURIComponent(searchTerm)}`;\\n  const apiResponse = await fetch(apiUrl);\\n  // ... follows URL from response\\n}\",\n      \"protocol_control\": \"NO (directly), FULL (via response URL chain)\",\n      \"host_control\": \"NO (directly), FULL (via response URL chain)\",\n      \"port_control\": \"NO (directly), FULL (via response URL chain)\",\n      \"path_control\": \"NO (directly), FULL (via response URL chain)\",\n      \"impact\": \"Allows querying the Strapi API with arbitrary search terms. Combined with stored malicious file URLs in Strapi, this could enable SSRF to internal services.\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Validate filename format before using in API queries. Validate URLs returned by the API against an allowlist of expected patterns.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}
