[2026-03-21 12:10:56] [pre-recon] [LLM] Turn 425: {"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Dp8G6Hix4C4B8ZwUGQ3A9P","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/deliverables/xss_analysis.md","content":"# XSS / Injection Sink Analysis Report\n\n**Application:** KamriHub E-Commerce Frontend (Next.js 14 App Router)\n**Date:** 2026-03-21\n**Scope:** All source files under `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/`\n\n---\n\n## EXECUTIVE SUMMARY\n\nThis analysis identified **17 distinct sink instances** across 13 files in the codebase. The most critical findings are:\n\n1. **innerHTML-based HTML entity decoding** of API-sourced review data (HIGH risk -- XSS via stored review content)\n2. **Broken sanitization utility** -- DOMPurify is referenced but NOT installed; the regex fallback in development mode can be bypassed (HIGH risk)\n3. **JSON-LD injection via dangerouslySetInnerHTML** with API-sourced product data that includes user-controllable fields (MEDIUM risk)\n4. **SSRF via proxy API routes** -- avatar and Strapi image proxies accept arbitrary path segments (MEDIUM risk)\n5. **Open redirect potential** in the Google OAuth callback redirect guard (MEDIUM risk)\n6. **Reflected search query** rendered directly in the DOM without encoding (LOW risk due to React auto-escaping, but defense-in-depth concern)\n\n---\n\n## 1. dangerouslySetInnerHTML USAGES (4 instances)\n\n### 1.1 Layout Scripts -- Google Consent Mode\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/layout-scripts.tsx`, line 33\n- **Code:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: consentModeScript }}`\n- **Data source:** Hardcoded string literal (lines 12-27)\n- **User input reachable:** NO -- constant string\n- **Render context:** script element in HTML head\n- **Risk:** LOW -- content is a static string, no user input flows into it\n\n### 1.2 Product JSON-LD\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/ProductJsonLd.tsx`, line 81\n- **Code:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}`\n- **Data source:** Product data from API: name, description, brand, images, price, currency, rating\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- product name, description, and brand originate from CJ Dropshipping and admin input. If a product name contains `</script><script>alert(1)</script>`, JSON.stringify would produce `\"</script><script>alert(1)</script>\"` which breaks out of the script tag.\n- **Render context:** `<script type=\"application/ld+json\">` tag\n- **Risk:** **MEDIUM** -- `JSON.stringify()` does NOT escape `</script>` sequences. An attacker who controls a product name or description (e.g., via CJ API injection or admin compromise) could inject `</script><script>...` to break out of the JSON-LD block. However, this requires backend compromise or malicious product data from the CJ supplier API.\n\n### 1.3 Breadcrumb JSON-LD\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/BreadcrumbJsonLd.tsx`, line 48\n- **Code:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}`\n- **Data source:** Product name, category name from API\n- **User input reachable:** Same as 1.2\n- **Render context:** `<script type=\"application/ld+json\">` tag\n- **Risk:** **MEDIUM** -- Same `</script>` breakout vector as 1.2\n\n### 1.4 Category ItemList JSON-LD\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/CategoryItemListJsonLd.tsx`, line 35\n- **Code:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}`\n- **Data source:** Product names, URLs from API\n- **User input reachable:** Same as 1.2\n- **Render context:** `<script type=\"application/ld+json\">` tag\n- **Risk:** **MEDIUM** -- Same `</script>` breakout vector as 1.2\n\n---\n\n## 2. innerHTML USAGES (2 instances) -- HIGHEST RISK\n\n### 2.1 ProductReviews -- decodeHtmlEntities\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/ProductReviews.tsx`, lines 12-14\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nfunction decodeHtmlEntities(text: string): string {\n  if (!text) return text;\n  const textArea = document.createElement('textarea');\n  textArea.innerHTML = text;  // LINE 13 -- XSS SINK\n  return textArea.value;\n}\n```\n- **Data source:** `review.comment` from CJ Product Reviews API (line 327: `{decodeHtmlEntities(review.comment)}`)\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- CJ product reviews are user-generated content from third-party buyers. The `comment` field contains arbitrary user text.\n- **Render context:** HTML body via innerHTML assignment to a textarea element\n- **Risk:** **HIGH** -- While the return value (`textArea.value`) extracts decoded text, the `innerHTML` assignment itself triggers HTML parsing. If `text` contains something like `<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>`, the browser will parse and execute the onerror handler during the innerHTML assignment, BEFORE `.value` is read. The textarea does NOT prevent script-executing tags during parsing. This is a **stored XSS** vulnerability.\n\n### 2.2 ProductReviewsModal -- decodeHtmlEntities (duplicate)\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/ProductReviewsModal.tsx`, lines 11-13\n- **Code:** Identical `decodeHtmlEntities` function\n- **Data source:** `review.comment` from unified reviews (line 258: `{decodeHtmlEntities(review.comment)}`)\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- same as 2.1\n- **Render context:** Same as 2.1\n- **Risk:** **HIGH** -- Same vulnerability as 2.1\n\n---\n\n## 3. eval / Function / setTimeout(string) / setInterval(string)\n\n**NO INSTANCES FOUND.** The codebase does not use eval(), new Function(), or string-based setTimeout/setInterval.\n\n---\n\n## 4. jQuery Sinks\n\n**NO jQuery FOUND.** jQuery is not a dependency and no jQuery selectors or methods are present.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Template Literal Injections into HTML\n\n### 5.1 Sitemap XML Generation\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/sitemap-xml.ts`, lines 34-37\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nlet xml = `  <url>\\n    <loc>${escapeXml(loc)}</loc>\\n`;\n```\n- **Data source:** Product slugs and URLs from API\n- **User input reachable:** Indirect (product slugs from admin/CJ data)\n- **Render context:** XML response (Content-Type: application/xml)\n- **Risk:** LOW -- `escapeXml()` is applied to all interpolated values\n\n### 5.2 sanitize.ts Regex Fallback\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/utils/sanitize.ts`, line 57\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nsanitized = sanitized.replace(openTag, `<${tag}>`).replace(closeTag, `</${tag}>`);\n```\n- **Data source:** HTML content passed to sanitizeHtml()\n- **Risk:** See Section 13 for detailed bypass analysis\n\n---\n\n## 6. Location/Navigation Sinks (DOM XSS Vectors)\n\n### 6.1 LanguageContext -- window.location.href assignment\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/contexts/LanguageContext.tsx`, lines 115, 126\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nconst url = productUrl + window.location.search + window.location.hash;\nwindow.location.href = url;\n```\n- **Data source:** `productUrl` is computed from product data (safe), but `window.location.search` and `window.location.hash` are appended verbatim\n- **User input reachable:** PARTIAL -- The base URL is controlled by the application, but search/hash are preserved from the current URL. Since this is NOT a `javascript:` protocol assignment (the base is a path), the risk is limited.\n- **Render context:** Navigation/URL\n- **Risk:** LOW -- The base path is always a product URL starting with `/`. No `javascript:` protocol injection possible.\n\n### 6.2 GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard -- window.location.replace\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard.tsx`, line 31\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nconst target = `/${locale}/auth/google/callback${search}${hash}`;\nwindow.location.replace(target);\n```\n- **Data source:** `window.location.search` and `window.location.hash` from current URL\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- attacker controls search and hash parameters\n- **Render context:** Navigation target\n- **Risk:** **MEDIUM** -- While the base path is fixed (`/{locale}/auth/google/callback`), the search and hash are injected verbatim. An attacker could craft a URL with a malicious hash/search parameter that is preserved during the redirect. However, since the target always starts with `/`, `javascript:` protocol injection is not possible. The main risk is parameter pollution or token theft via open redirect chains.\n\n### 6.3 ProductClient -- window.location.replace for slug normalization\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/ProductClient.tsx`, line 93\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nwindow.location.replace(expected + window.location.search + window.location.hash);\n```\n- **Data source:** `expected` from `getProductUrl()` (computed from product data), plus current URL's search and hash\n- **User input reachable:** PARTIAL -- same as 6.1\n- **Risk:** LOW -- base path is always a product URL\n\n### 6.4 AuthModal -- window.location.href for Google OAuth\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/AuthModal.tsx`, line 746\n- **Code:** `window.location.href = googleAuthUrl;`\n- **Data source:** `getApiBaseUrl()` + `/auth/google` -- from environment variable\n- **User input reachable:** NO -- URL is constructed from env var\n- **Risk:** LOW\n\n### 6.5 Google OAuth Callback -- window.location.href for retry\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx`, line 178\n- **Code:** `window.location.href = googleAuthUrl;`\n- **Data source:** `getApiBaseUrl()` -- environment variable\n- **User input reachable:** NO\n- **Risk:** LOW\n\n### 6.6 Other static redirects\n- **Files:** `OrdersHistoryNew.tsx:307`, `AccountSettingsNew.tsx:328`, `ModernHeader.tsx:1070`\n- **Code:** `window.location.href = '/products'`, `window.location.href = '/'`\n- **User input reachable:** NO -- hardcoded paths\n- **Risk:** LOW\n\n---\n\n## 7. URL Parameter / Query String / Hash Reading and Rendering\n\n### 7.1 Google OAuth Callback -- Token from URL/Hash\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx`, lines 16-36\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nfunction parseTokenFromUrl(searchParams: URLSearchParams) {\n  let token = searchParams.get('token');\n  // Also reads from window.location.hash and window.location.search\n  const hash = window.location.hash || '';\n  const params = new URLSearchParams(hash.replace(/^#/, ''));\n  token = token || params.get('token');\n}\n```\n- **Data source:** URL query params and hash fragment\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- attacker can craft URL with arbitrary token/error/reason params\n- **Render context:** Token is stored via `setAuthToken(token)` (localStorage), error/reason are used as keys into translation map (not rendered raw)\n- **Risk:** **MEDIUM** -- The token value from URL is stored directly into localStorage and set as the API auth token. An attacker could craft a URL like `?token=MALICIOUS_JWT` to inject an arbitrary JWT. However, this is a **session fixation** concern rather than XSS. The error and reason codes are only used as keys to look up translations, so they are not directly rendered.\n\n### 7.2 Newsletter Confirm -- Token from URL\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/newsletter/confirm/page.tsx`, lines 19-20\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nconst url = new URL(window.location.href);\nconst token = url.searchParams.get('token');\n```\n- **Data source:** URL query param `token`\n- **User input reachable:** YES\n- **Render context:** Used in API call URL (with encodeURIComponent): `fetch(buildUrl(\\`/newsletter/confirm?token=\\${encodeURIComponent(token)}\\`))`\n- **Risk:** LOW -- properly encoded before use in URL\n\n### 7.3 Search Page -- Query Reflection\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/search/page.tsx`, lines 47, 141, 212\n- **Code:**\n```tsx\nconst query = searchParams.get('q') || '';\n// Line 141:\n<h1>Resultats de recherche pour \"{query}\"</h1>\n// Line 212:\n<p>Nous n'avons trouve aucun produit ou categorie correspondant a \"{query}\"</p>\n```\n- **Data source:** URL query param `q`\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- directly from URL\n- **Render context:** HTML body (React JSX text node)\n- **Risk:** LOW -- React automatically escapes JSX text content, preventing XSS. However, this is a reflected user input pattern that should use explicit sanitization as defense-in-depth.\n\n### 7.4 Auth Page -- Redirect Parameter\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/auth/page.tsx`, lines 30-32\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nconst redirect = searchParams.get('redirect');\nconst safePath = safeRedirect(redirect);\n```\n- **Data source:** URL query param `redirect`\n- **User input reachable:** YES\n- **Render context:** Used for router.replace navigation\n- **Risk:** LOW -- `safeRedirect()` properly validates the path starts with `/` and rejects `//`, `http://`, `https://`\n\n### 7.5 Middleware -- Bypass Code from URL\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/middleware.ts`, line 127\n- **Code:** `const urlBypass = request.nextUrl.searchParams.get('bypass');`\n- **Data source:** URL query param `bypass`\n- **User input reachable:** YES\n- **Render context:** Compared to env var, then stored in cookie\n- **Risk:** LOW -- used only for maintenance bypass comparison, not rendered\n\n---\n\n## 8. Components That Accept and Render HTML Props\n\n### 8.1 ProductReviews -- cjReviews prop (JSON string)\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/ProductReviews.tsx`, line 37\n- **Code:** `cjReviews?: string; // JSON string des avis CJ depuis le produit`\n- **Data flow:** `cjReviews` is a JSON string from the product API -> `JSON.parse(cjReviews)` -> array of review objects -> `review.comment` -> `decodeHtmlEntities()` -> rendered as text node\n- **Risk:** HIGH -- as documented in Section 2, `decodeHtmlEntities` uses innerHTML\n\n### 8.2 ProductTabs -- description prop\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/ProductTabs.tsx`\n- **Code:** `description?: string` prop, rendered through `formatDescription()` which splits text and renders in JSX text nodes\n- **Data flow:** Product description from API -> text processing (regex-based) -> JSX text content\n- **Risk:** LOW -- `formatDescription()` uses React JSX text nodes (auto-escaped), not dangerouslySetInnerHTML. No innerHTML usage.\n\n---\n\n## 9. SQL Injection Points\n\n**NONE FOUND.** This is a frontend application. No database queries are made directly. All data access goes through `apiClient` HTTP calls to the NestJS backend API.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Command Injection Points\n\n**NONE FOUND.** No `exec`, `spawn`, `execSync`, `spawnSync`, or `child_process` imports exist in the `/src` directory.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Template Injection Points\n\n**NONE FOUND.** No server-side template engines (EJS, Handlebars, Pug, etc.) are used. The application is a React/Next.js app that uses JSX for rendering.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Deserialization Sinks\n\n### 12.1 JSON.parse of cjReviews\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/ProductReviews.tsx`, line 78\n- **Code:** `const parsedReviews = typeof cjReviews === 'string' ? JSON.parse(cjReviews) : cjReviews;`\n- **Data source:** `cjReviews` prop from product API data\n- **User input reachable:** Indirect -- API response data\n- **Risk:** LOW -- JSON.parse is safe from code execution. The risk is in how the parsed data is subsequently used (see Section 2).\n\n### 12.2 JSON.parse of JWT payload\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/security/jwt.ts`, line 9\n- **Code:** `const payload = JSON.parse(atob(parts[1]));`\n- **Data source:** JWT token (from URL or localStorage)\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- tokens from URL in OAuth callback\n- **Risk:** LOW -- Only checks `exp` field, no execution of parsed data. Wrapped in try/catch.\n\n### 12.3 JSON.parse of localStorage data\n- **Files:** `localStorageCart.ts:23`, `localStorageWishlist.ts:16`\n- **Code:** `return JSON.parse(stored);`\n- **Data source:** localStorage (client-side storage)\n- **User input reachable:** Only via XSS (attacker already has script execution)\n- **Risk:** LOW\n\n---\n\n## 13. File Path Manipulation\n\n### 13.1 Avatar Proxy -- Path Traversal\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts`, lines 14-15\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nconst { path } = await params;\nconst imagePath = path.join('/');\n```\n- **Data source:** URL path segments from request\n- **User input reachable:** YES -- attacker controls the path: `/api/avatar/../../etc/passwd`\n- **Render context:** Used to construct fetch URLs to Supabase/backend: `\\`${serverUrl}/uploads/users/${imagePath}\\``\n- **Risk:** **MEDIUM** -- This is a **Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)** vector. The `imagePath` is user-controlled path segments joined with `/`. While Next.js catch-all routes may normalize `..` segments, an attacker could craft paths like `/api/avatar/..%2F..%2Fetc%2Fpasswd` or use the path to probe internal services. The proxy fetches the URL and returns the response body.\n\n### 13.2 Strapi Image Proxy -- Path Traversal + SSRF\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts`, lines 13-15\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nconst { path } = await params;\nconst imagePath = path.join('/');\n```\n- **Data source:** URL path segments + query params (searchParams `id`)\n- **User input reachable:** YES\n- **Render context:** Used to construct fetch URLs to Strapi: `\\`${baseUrl}${imagePath.startsWith('/') ? imagePath : \\`/\\${imagePath}\\`}\\``\n- **Risk:** **MEDIUM** -- Same SSRF concern as 13.1. Additionally, the `id` query parameter is used directly in API calls to Strapi (`/api/upload/files/${fileId}`) without validation.\n\n### 13.3 Sitemaps.txt -- readFile (Static)\n- **File:** `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/sitemaps.txt/route.ts`, lines 8-10\n- **Code:**\n```typescript\nconst rootPath = path.join(process.cwd(), 'sitemaps.txt');\nconst txt = await readFile(rootPath, 'utf8');\n```\n- **Data source:** Static file path (process.cwd() + 'sitemaps.txt')\n- **User input reachable:** NO -- hardcoded path\n- **Risk:** LOW -- no user input in file path\n\n---\n\n## 14. Sanitization Utility Analysis -- CRITICAL FINDINGS\n\n### File: `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/utils/sanitize.ts`\n\n**CRITICAL ISSUE #1: DOMPurify is NOT installed**\n\nThe `sanitizeHtml()` function references `window.DOMPurify` but DOMPurify is **NOT in package.json dependencies**. This means the DOMPurify codepath NEVER executes. The function ALWAYS falls through to the regex-based fallback.\n\n**CRITICAL ISSUE #2: Development mode regex fallback is bypassable**\n\nIn development mode (lines 45-58), the function:\n1. Escapes all `<`, `>`, `\"`, `'`, `/` characters\n2. Then re-allows specific tags by converting `&lt;tag&gt;` back to `<tag>`\n\nThe allowed tags include `span` and `div`. The regex that re-allows tags is:\n```typescript\nconst openTag = new RegExp(`&lt;${tag}&gt;`, 'gi');\n```\n\nThis only matches `<tag>` (simple open tags without attributes). Since attributes are NOT supported, `<span onclick=...>` would NOT be restored. However, the allowlist includes `div` and `span` -- if the regex were extended to support attributes, this would be dangerous.\n\n**Current bypass status: The dev-mode fallback is SAFE by accident** -- it only restores bare tags without attributes, so no event handlers can be injected. But the architecture is fragile: any future modification to support tag attributes would create an XSS hole.\n\n**CRITICAL ISSUE #3: Production fallback is escape-only**\n\nIn production (lines 72-77), when DOMPurify is not available (which is always), the function escapes everything:\n```typescript\nreturn html.replace(/</g, '&lt;').replace(/>/g, '&gt;')...\n```\n\nThis makes the output safe from XSS but **strips all HTML formatting**, rendering the function useless for its intended purpose of allowing safe HTML tags.\n\n**CRITICAL ISSUE #4: sanitizeHtml() is NOT used anywhere**\n\nSearching the codebase, `sanitizeHtml` from `sanitize.ts` is **never imported or called** in any component or page. The only sanitization actually used is:\n- `sanitizeText` from `validation.ts` (strips HTML tags with `/<[^>]*>/g` regex -- used for form input validation)\n- `sanitizeCarrierName` in `OrdersHistoryNew.tsx` (specific to carrier name cleaning)\n\nThe product descriptions and review comments bypass the sanitization utility entirely.\n\n---\n\n## 15. Content Security Policy Analysis\n\n### File: `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/middleware.ts`, lines 64-75\n\n```\nscript-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' 'unsafe-eval' https://m.stripe.network https://js.stripe.com ...\n```\n\n**CRITICAL:** The CSP includes both `'unsafe-inline'` AND `'unsafe-eval'` in `script-src`. This means:\n- `'unsafe-inline'` allows inline `<script>` tags and inline event handlers -- completely negating CSP protection against XSS\n- `'unsafe-eval'` allows `eval()`, `new Function()`, and `setTimeout(string)` -- if an attacker achieves injection, they can execute arbitrary code\n\nThe comment in middleware.ts acknowledges this: \"Note: 'unsafe-inline' / 'unsafe-eval' are required for Next.js runtime and dev HMR; remove when using nonce-based CSP.\"\n\n**Impact:** The weak CSP means that any XSS injection (such as via the innerHTML sinks in ProductReviews) would succeed without CSP blocking it.\n\n---\n\n## 16. safeRedirect Utility Analysis\n\n### File: `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/security/safeRedirect.ts`\n\n```typescript\nexport function safeRedirect(redirect?: string | null): string {\n  if (!redirect || typeof redirect !== 'string') return '/';\n  const trimmed = redirect.trim();\n  if (!trimmed.startsWith('/')) return '/';\n  if (trimmed.startsWith('//')) return '/';\n  if (/^https?:\\/\\//i.test(trimmed)) return '/';\n  return trimmed;\n}\n```\n\n**Analysis:** This function is **well-implemented** for its purpose. It:\n- Rejects non-string/empty inputs\n- Requires path to start with `/`\n- Blocks protocol-relative URLs (`//evil.com`)\n- Blocks absolute URLs (`http://` and `https://`)\n\n**Minor concern:** Does not block `javascript:` or `data:` URIs, but since it requires the path to start with `/`, these cannot be injected. The function is sound.\n\n---\n\n## VULNERABILITY SUMMARY TABLE\n\n| # | Sink Type | File | Line | Risk | User Input? | Exploitable? |\n|---|-----------|------|------|------|-------------|--------------|\n| 1 | innerHTML | ProductReviews.tsx | 13 | **HIGH** | YES (CJ reviews) | YES -- stored XSS via review comments |\n| 2 | innerHTML | ProductReviewsModal.tsx | 12 | **HIGH** | YES (CJ reviews) | YES -- stored XSS via review comments |\n| 3 | dangerouslySetInnerHTML | ProductJsonLd.tsx | 81 | MEDIUM | YES (product data) | Requires backend/CJ API compromise |\n| 4 | dangerouslySetInnerHTML | BreadcrumbJsonLd.tsx | 48 | MEDIUM | YES (product data) | Requires backend/CJ API compromise |\n| 5 | dangerouslySetInnerHTML | CategoryItemListJsonLd.tsx | 35 | MEDIUM | YES (product data) | Requires backend/CJ API compromise |\n| 6 | dangerouslySetInnerHTML | layout-scripts.tsx | 33 | LOW | NO (static) | No |\n| 7 | window.location.replace | GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard.tsx | 31 | MEDIUM | YES (URL params) | Open redirect/param injection |\n| 8 | SSRF/Path traversal | avatar/[...path]/route.ts | 15 | MEDIUM | YES (URL path) | SSRF to internal services |\n| 9 | SSRF/Path traversal | strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts | 15 | MEDIUM | YES (URL path) | SSRF to internal services |\n| 10 | Session fixation | auth/google/callback/page.tsx | 94 | MEDIUM | YES (URL token) | JWT injection via crafted URL |\n| 11 | Reflected query | search/page.tsx | 141 | LOW | YES (URL param q) | React auto-escapes (safe) |\n| 12 | Broken sanitizer | sanitize.ts | all | **HIGH** | N/A | DOMPurify missing; regex fallback |\n| 13 | Weak CSP | middleware.ts | 66 | **HIGH** | N/A | unsafe-inline + unsafe-eval |\n\n---\n\n## RECOMMENDATIONS (Priority Order)\n\n1. **CRITICAL -- Fix innerHTML XSS in ProductReviews**: Replace `decodeHtmlEntities()` with a safe approach. Either:\n   - Use a DOMParser-based approach that does not execute scripts: `new DOMParser().parseFromString(text, 'text/html').body.textContent`\n   - Or simply use the `he` npm package for HTML entity decoding without DOM parsing\n\n2. **CRITICAL -- Install DOMPurify**: Add `dompurify` to package.json and import it properly in `sanitize.ts`\n\n3. **CRITICAL -- Remove unsafe-inline/unsafe-eval from CSP**: Implement nonce-based CSP for Next.js scripts\n\n4. **HIGH -- Sanitize JSON-LD output**: Use `JSON.stringify(jsonLd).replace(/</g, '\\\\u003c')` to prevent `</script>` breakout in JSON-LD script tags\n\n5. **MEDIUM -- Add SSRF protection to proxy routes**: Validate that the requested path does not contain `..` segments and that the final URL resolves to expected domains only\n\n6. **MEDIUM -- Add URL validation in GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard**: Sanitize search/hash params or use a whitelist of expected parameters\n\n7. **LOW -- Add explicit escaping for reflected search query**: Even though React auto-escapes, apply `escapeHtml()` as defense-in-depth\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}
