[2026-03-21 12:20:01] [pre-recon] [LLM] Turn 458: {"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AcxggYGQYKgAF2gSBtSm9o","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/DATA_SECURITY_AUDIT.json","content":"{\n  \"vulnerabilities\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-001\",\n      \"title\": \"Supabase service_role JWT committed in local .env (accessible to all developers)\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"type\": \"CREDENTIAL_EXPOSURE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/.env\",\n      \"line\": 15,\n      \"details\": \"The .env file contains SUPABASE_KEY with a full service_role JWT (eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIs...) for project fzcgqswwhvukwrawfhev.supabase.co. This key grants full admin access to Supabase: it bypasses RLS, can read/write/delete any data in any table, manage auth users, and access storage. While .env is gitignored and not tracked, any developer with repo checkout access has this key on disk. If the .env template is shared or the file is accidentally committed in the future, the blast radius is total Supabase compromise.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"service_role_key\", \"database_admin_credential\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Rotate this key immediately. Move it to a secrets manager (Vercel env, Railway env, Vault). Ensure .env is never committed. Consider using Supabase anon key for client-side and service_role only in server-side backend.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-002\",\n      \"title\": \"Strapi license key committed in local .env\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"CREDENTIAL_EXPOSURE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/.env\",\n      \"line\": 39,\n      \"details\": \"STRAPI_LICENSE contains a long base64-encoded license key. While not a runtime security vulnerability, license keys are proprietary secrets that should not be in shared configuration files.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"license_key\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Move to a secrets manager or CI/CD environment variables.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-003\",\n      \"title\": \"Maintenance bypass code hardcoded as fallback in middleware source code\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"type\": \"HARDCODED_SECRET\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/middleware.ts\",\n      \"line\": 126,\n      \"details\": \"The maintenance bypass code has a hardcoded fallback: `process.env.MAINTENANCE_BYPASS_CODE || 'dev-bypass-2024'`. If the environment variable is not set in production (common oversight), anyone can bypass maintenance mode by visiting any URL with ?bypass=dev-bypass-2024. This default is present in the committed source code, visible to anyone with repo access.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"bypass_code\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Remove the hardcoded fallback. If the env var is not set, maintenance bypass should be disabled entirely.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-004\",\n      \"title\": \"Auth token (JWT) stored in localStorage -- vulnerable to XSS exfiltration\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"type\": \"TOKEN_STORAGE_XSS\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/secureToken.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [34, 35, 54],\n      \"details\": \"The authentication JWT is stored in localStorage under key 'auth_token' (line 34) and 'auth_token_created_at' (line 35). While the code maintains an in-memory copy (memoryToken) for faster access, it always persists to localStorage for page-reload survival (line 34). Any XSS vulnerability anywhere in the application would allow an attacker to run localStorage.getItem('auth_token') and exfiltrate the JWT. The code comments acknowledge this risk but accept it for UX reasons. The token contains the user's identity and grants full API access.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"jwt_token\", \"session_credential\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Use httpOnly cookies for token storage instead of localStorage. This prevents JavaScript access entirely. If localStorage must be used, implement a token rotation mechanism and short expiry times.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-005\",\n      \"title\": \"Auth token transmitted in URL query/fragment during Google OAuth callback\",\n      \"severity\": \"HIGH\",\n      \"type\": \"TOKEN_IN_URL\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx\",\n      \"lines\": [17, 22, 23, 29, 30, 31, 32, 33],\n      \"details\": \"After Google OAuth, the backend redirects to the callback page with the JWT token as a URL query parameter (?token=...) or hash fragment (#token=...). The parseTokenFromUrl function (line 16-37) extracts it from both locations. Tokens in URLs are logged in browser history, server access logs, referrer headers, and potentially analytics. The GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard component (src/components/GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard.tsx line 30) also logs the redirect target containing the token via console.log. While history.replaceState is called later (line 124), there is a window where the token is visible in the URL bar and browser history.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"jwt_token\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Use a short-lived authorization code exchanged server-side for a token, rather than passing the JWT directly in the URL. At minimum, clear the URL immediately before any other processing.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-006\",\n      \"title\": \"Google OAuth callback logs user PII (userId, email) to browser console in production\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"PII_LEAKAGE_CONSOLE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx\",\n      \"line\": 200,\n      \"details\": \"Line 200 uses raw console.log (not the dev-only logger utility): `console.log('[Google OAuth] 7. Profil disponible...', { userId: user?.id, email: user?.email })`. This logs the authenticated user's ID and email address to the browser console in ALL environments including production. Multiple other console.log calls in this file (lines 80, 93, 107, 129, 137, 144, 150, 159, 165) also run in production but log less sensitive data (token presence booleans, not actual token values).\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"user_id\", \"email_address\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Replace all console.log calls in this file with the logger utility from /repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/utils/logger.ts which only logs in development mode.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-007\",\n      \"title\": \"Contact form PII (name, email, phone) persisted in localStorage as draft\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"PII_IN_BROWSER_STORAGE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/ContactForm.tsx\",\n      \"lines\": [48, 62, 63, 64, 65, 66, 67, 68, 69],\n      \"details\": \"The contact form auto-saves drafts to localStorage every 2 seconds under key 'contactFormDraft' (line 62). The saved data includes name, email, phone, subject, message, and orderNumber -- all PII. This data persists indefinitely in the browser (no TTL) even after form submission fails or user navigates away without submitting. It is cleared only on successful submission (line 132). On shared or public computers, this PII remains accessible to the next user.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"name\", \"email\", \"phone_number\", \"order_number\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Add a TTL to draft storage (e.g., 30 minutes). Clear the draft on page unload. Consider encrypting the stored data or at minimum not persisting phone/email.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-008\",\n      \"title\": \"Google Maps API key exposed in client-side JavaScript via NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"API_KEY_EXPOSURE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/.env\",\n      \"line\": 34,\n      \"details\": \"NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY=AIzaSyCtlI5rM3SYATTYTHhbKXgCcTkK7B44sbE is exposed to all browser clients. In AddressAutocomplete.tsx (line 47), this key is embedded directly into a script tag URL: `https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=${apiKey}&libraries=places`. Anyone can extract this key from the page source and use it for their own Google Maps API calls, incurring charges on the project's billing account. The key appears to have at least the Places API enabled.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"api_key\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Restrict this API key in Google Cloud Console: set HTTP referrer restrictions to your production domains only. Set API restrictions to only the Places API. Set a daily quota limit to prevent abuse.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-009\",\n      \"title\": \"Stripe test publishable key exposed via NEXT_PUBLIC_ (expected but verify production)\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"API_KEY_EXPOSURE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/.env\",\n      \"line\": 21,\n      \"details\": \"NEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=pk_test_51SU1sPQtRP... is a Stripe TEST publishable key exposed to the browser. Publishable keys are designed to be client-facing and can only create tokens/confirm payments -- they cannot charge cards or access account data. However, the /api/stripe/config route (src/app/api/stripe/config/route.ts line 5) also exposes this via a separate API endpoint, creating a second exposure vector. Ensure the production deployment uses a live publishable key (pk_live_...) and NEVER the secret key (sk_...).\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"stripe_publishable_key\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Verify that the production environment uses pk_live_ (not pk_test_). Ensure sk_live_ or sk_test_ secret keys are NEVER in NEXT_PUBLIC_ variables.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-010\",\n      \"title\": \"HTML sanitization has a conditional DOMPurify dependency with weak regex fallback\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"XSS_SANITIZATION_WEAKNESS\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/utils/sanitize.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [31, 44, 45, 46, 47, 48, 49, 50, 51, 53, 54, 55, 56, 57],\n      \"details\": \"The sanitizeHtml function in sanitize.ts relies on DOMPurify as an optional dependency (window.DOMPurify). If DOMPurify is not loaded (which appears to be the case as it is not in the dependency list), the fallback (lines 44-58) uses a regex-based approach that first escapes all HTML, then re-enables specific tags via regex replacement. This is fragile: the regex only matches simple tags like <b> but not tags with attributes (<b class='x'>), and the re-allowlisting approach can be bypassed with creative payloads. In production without DOMPurify (lines 71-77), it falls back to escaping everything, which is safe but means the allowlisted tags in the comment are misleading.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"html_content\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Add DOMPurify as an explicit dependency (npm install dompurify). Import and use it deterministically rather than checking window.DOMPurify at runtime.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-011\",\n      \"title\": \"dangerouslySetInnerHTML used in JSON-LD scripts with product data from API\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"XSS_RISK\",\n      \"files\": [\n        \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/CategoryItemListJsonLd.tsx:35\",\n        \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/ProductJsonLd.tsx:81\",\n        \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/BreadcrumbJsonLd.tsx:48\",\n        \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/layout-scripts.tsx:33\"\n      ],\n      \"details\": \"dangerouslySetInnerHTML is used in 4 locations. Three of them (CategoryItemListJsonLd, ProductJsonLd, BreadcrumbJsonLd) pass API-sourced data through JSON.stringify() into <script type='application/ld+json'> tags. JSON.stringify provides some protection by escaping quotes, but if product names contain </script> sequences, they could break out of the script context. The layout-scripts.tsx usage injects a consent mode initialization script.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"product_data\", \"category_data\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Sanitize product/category names before JSON-LD generation. Ensure JSON.stringify output is safe for script context by escaping </script> and <!-- sequences.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-012\",\n      \"title\": \"Avatar proxy route has no path traversal protection (potential SSRF)\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"SSRF_PATH_TRAVERSAL\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [15, 52],\n      \"details\": \"The avatar proxy route takes a catch-all path parameter and reconstructs it into URLs for fetching. On line 15, `const imagePath = path.join('/')` joins all path segments. On line 52, this is interpolated into `${serverUrl}/uploads/users/${imagePath}`. If the path contains segments like '../../' or encoded traversal characters, it could potentially be used to fetch arbitrary paths from the backend server or Supabase storage. The same applies to Supabase URL construction (lines 26-31). Additionally, line 89 sets `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: '*'` which allows any origin to fetch avatars through this proxy.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"file_path\", \"server_url\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Validate that imagePath matches expected avatar filename patterns (e.g., UUID + extension). Reject paths containing '..' or other traversal patterns. Remove the wildcard CORS header or restrict it to the application's own origin.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-013\",\n      \"title\": \"Account deletion feature is non-functional (UI only, no backend call in old component)\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"GDPR_COMPLIANCE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/AccountSettings.tsx\",\n      \"line\": 59,\n      \"details\": \"The AccountSettings component (old version) has a handleDeleteAccount function at line 58-60 that only does `console.log('Suppression du compte demandée')` -- no actual API call. A newer AccountSettingsNew.tsx (line 322) does call `apiClient.deleteUserAccount()`. However, if the old component is still rendered anywhere, users clicking 'Delete my account' would believe their data was deleted when it was not. This is a GDPR Article 17 (right to erasure) compliance issue.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"user_account\", \"all_pii\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Ensure only AccountSettingsNew.tsx is used in the active profile page. Remove or update the old AccountSettings.tsx. Verify the backend actually deletes all user data when deleteUserAccount is called.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-014\",\n      \"title\": \"Password fields still present in login/register API methods despite OTP-primary auth\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"UNNECESSARY_DATA_COLLECTION\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/api.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [184, 191, 270, 277],\n      \"details\": \"The ApiClient has login(email, password) at line 184 and register(email, name, password) at line 270 that send password in the request body. The application prominently claims 'No password stored' (security constants) and uses OTP as the primary auth flow. However, these password-based endpoints still exist and are callable. If passwords are transmitted, they are sent over HTTPS to the backend. The register endpoint also sends role: 'user' in the body (line 277), which could be tampered with if the backend trusts this field.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"password\", \"user_role\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"If OTP is the only supported auth method, remove the password-based login and register methods. If they must remain, ensure the backend ignores the role field from client input.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-015\",\n      \"title\": \"CSP uses unsafe-inline and unsafe-eval for scripts\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"WEAK_CSP\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/middleware.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [66, 67],\n      \"details\": \"The Content-Security-Policy header (line 66) includes `'unsafe-inline' 'unsafe-eval'` in the script-src directive. This significantly weakens XSS protection because any inline script injection would be allowed by the CSP. The comment on line 63 acknowledges this: 'unsafe-inline / unsafe-eval are required for Next.js runtime and dev HMR'. While this is a common Next.js limitation, it means CSP provides no meaningful XSS mitigation.\",\n      \"data_types\": [],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Implement nonce-based CSP for Next.js. Use @next/headers to generate per-request nonces and apply them to script tags. This allows removing unsafe-inline and unsafe-eval.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-016\",\n      \"title\": \"Maintenance bypass cookie not cryptographically secure\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"WEAK_AUTHENTICATION\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/middleware.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [131, 137, 138, 139, 140, 141],\n      \"details\": \"The maintenance bypass works by comparing a plaintext code (line 131: urlBypass === bypassCode). Once matched, a cookie is set with the plaintext bypass code as its value (line 137). The cookie is httpOnly and secure in production, but the bypass code itself is a simple static string comparison. If the bypass code is known (and it defaults to 'dev-bypass-2024' per DS-003), anyone can set this cookie manually.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"bypass_credential\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Use a signed/HMAC'd token for the bypass cookie rather than storing the raw bypass code.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-017\",\n      \"title\": \"Client-side rate limiter is trivially bypassable\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"WEAK_RATE_LIMITING\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/rateLimiter.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [17, 22, 30],\n      \"details\": \"The rate limiter uses localStorage to track request timestamps (line 22, 30). An attacker can simply clear localStorage or use private browsing to bypass all rate limits. The code comments (line 6) correctly note this is 'frontend only' protection. However, if backend rate limiting is insufficient, this provides no real protection against OTP brute-force, contact form spam, or API abuse.\",\n      \"data_types\": [],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Ensure the backend has robust rate limiting (IP-based, account-based). The frontend rate limiter should be treated as UX guidance only, never as a security control.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-018\",\n      \"title\": \"Order data accessible from order-confirmation page via orderId URL parameter\",\n      \"severity\": \"MEDIUM\",\n      \"type\": \"AUTHORIZATION_BYPASS_RISK\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/order-confirmation/page.tsx\",\n      \"line\": 37,\n      \"details\": \"The order confirmation page reads `orderId` from URL search params (line 37) and fetches order data from the API. If the backend does not enforce that the requesting user owns the order (or require authentication for order lookup), any user who guesses or enumerates order IDs could view other users' order details including: shipping address, items purchased, pricing, and payment status. The component does import useAuth but the actual authorization check depends entirely on the backend API.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"order_details\", \"shipping_address\", \"purchase_history\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Verify the backend requires authentication AND ownership validation for order detail endpoints. Consider using non-sequential, UUID-based order IDs to prevent enumeration.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-019\",\n      \"title\": \"Supabase anon/publishable key uses non-standard naming convention\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"CONFIGURATION_CONCERN\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/.env\",\n      \"line\": 14,\n      \"details\": \"NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_DEFAULT_KEY=sb_publishable_k9xwMmz5rhGGZH4m5CFEjQ_mM3OEY3s uses a non-standard key format. Standard Supabase anon keys are JWTs (eyJ...). This 'sb_publishable_' prefixed key may be a custom obfuscation or a different Supabase project configuration. This key is browser-exposed (NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix) and points to a DIFFERENT Supabase project (ayeiqxvlzetfpipjzjta.supabase.co) than the service_role key (fzcgqswwhvukwrawfhev.supabase.co on line 16). The mismatch suggests either a migration in progress or misconfiguration.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"api_key\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Verify this key is correct and intentional. Ensure the two different Supabase project URLs are expected. Document the architecture if two Supabase projects are intentionally used.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-020\",\n      \"title\": \"Company PII and contact details in .env file\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"INFORMATION_EXPOSURE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/.env\",\n      \"lines\": [41, 42, 43, 44, 45],\n      \"details\": \"The .env file contains company details: SUPPORT_EMAIL=support@kamrihub.com, SUPPORT_PHONE=0466226183, COMPANY_ADDRESS=Rue Vanderstraetern 37 1080 BE, COMPANY_SIRET=123 456 789 00012, COMPANY_RCS=Paris B 123 456 789. While these may be public information, storing them in .env mixes secrets with non-secrets, increasing the risk of accidental exposure of the entire file.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"email\", \"phone_number\", \"physical_address\", \"business_registration\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Move non-secret company information to a constants file or CMS. Reserve .env exclusively for actual secrets and environment-specific configuration.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-021\",\n      \"title\": \"Session order data stored in sessionStorage with potential cross-tab leakage\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"DATA_IN_BROWSER_STORAGE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/cart/page.tsx\",\n      \"lines\": [503, 511, 512, 556, 557, 583, 584, 632, 633],\n      \"details\": \"The cart/checkout page stores pending order IDs and order numbers in sessionStorage. While sessionStorage is tab-scoped (better than localStorage), the order IDs stored could potentially be used to look up order details. The code does scope keys by userId (line 503 comment mentions 'HARDENING: scoped by env + userId'), which is a positive pattern.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"order_id\", \"order_number\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"This is a reasonable pattern. Ensure the backend validates ownership when these order IDs are used for lookups.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-022\",\n      \"title\": \"Google OAuth return URL stored in sessionStorage without validation\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"OPEN_REDIRECT_RISK\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/AuthModal.tsx\",\n      \"line\": 731,\n      \"details\": \"Before redirecting to Google OAuth, the current page URL is stored in sessionStorage as 'google_auth_return_url' (line 731). After OAuth callback, this URL is read (src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx line 105) and used for router.push(). While a safeRedirect utility exists at /repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/security/safeRedirect.ts, it is NOT used for this return URL. If an attacker can control the sessionStorage value (XSS), they could redirect the user to a malicious site after authentication.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"redirect_url\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Apply the safeRedirect() function to the return URL before using it for navigation. Validate it starts with '/' and does not contain protocol-relative URLs.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-023\",\n      \"title\": \"Cookie consent stored in localStorage (not in a cookie) -- may not satisfy GDPR technical requirements\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"GDPR_COMPLIANCE\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/cookieConsent.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [54, 109],\n      \"details\": \"Cookie consent preferences are stored in localStorage under key 'cookie_consent' rather than in an actual cookie. This means: (1) server-side rendering cannot check consent before including tracking scripts, (2) the consent state is not sent with HTTP requests, so server-side analytics cannot respect it, (3) some GDPR frameworks expect consent to be verifiable server-side. The implementation does include accept/reject/customize options and Google Consent Mode v2 integration.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"consent_preferences\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Additionally store consent in an httpOnly cookie so server-side code can check consent before embedding tracking scripts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-024\",\n      \"title\": \"Stripe payment flow properly delegates card handling to Stripe.js (POSITIVE)\",\n      \"severity\": \"INFO\",\n      \"type\": \"POSITIVE_FINDING\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/checkout/PaymentStep.tsx\",\n      \"details\": \"The Stripe integration follows best practices: (1) Payment intents are created server-side via apiClient.createPaymentIntent (line 124), (2) The clientSecret is passed to the frontend for Stripe.js confirmation (line 138-139), (3) Raw card numbers never touch the application server, (4) SavedCard objects only contain brand, last4, expMonth, expYear -- never full card numbers (lines 13-18). The StripeProvider correctly loads Stripe.js from the CDN. Card data is handled entirely within Stripe's PCI-compliant iframe.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"payment_data\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"No action needed. This is a correct implementation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-025\",\n      \"title\": \"Security headers properly implemented (POSITIVE)\",\n      \"severity\": \"INFO\",\n      \"type\": \"POSITIVE_FINDING\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/middleware.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [79, 80, 81, 82, 83, 84, 85],\n      \"details\": \"The middleware applies security headers to all responses: X-Frame-Options: DENY (prevents clickjacking), X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff (prevents MIME sniffing), Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin (limits referrer leakage), X-DNS-Prefetch-Control: off, Permissions-Policy: camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=(). These are well-configured.\",\n      \"data_types\": [],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Consider adding Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) header for HTTPS enforcement.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-026\",\n      \"title\": \"JWT expiry check implemented client-side (POSITIVE)\",\n      \"severity\": \"INFO\",\n      \"type\": \"POSITIVE_FINDING\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/security/jwt.ts\",\n      \"lines\": [5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],\n      \"details\": \"The isJwtExpired function checks the JWT exp claim client-side to avoid sending expired tokens. Combined with the 24-hour session max duration in AuthContext (SESSION_MAX_DURATION at src/contexts/AuthContext.tsx line 14), this provides defense-in-depth for token expiry. The getAuthToken function in secureToken.ts (line 60) calls isJwtExpired and clears expired tokens automatically.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"jwt_token\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"No action needed. Note this is client-side only -- the backend must also validate token expiry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-027\",\n      \"title\": \"Open redirect protection implemented (POSITIVE)\",\n      \"severity\": \"INFO\",\n      \"type\": \"POSITIVE_FINDING\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/security/safeRedirect.ts\",\n      \"details\": \"The safeRedirect utility validates redirect URLs: rejects absolute URLs, protocol-relative URLs, and non-path values. However, as noted in DS-022, it is not consistently applied to all redirect scenarios.\",\n      \"data_types\": [],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Apply safeRedirect to ALL user-controlled redirect targets, including the Google OAuth return URL.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-028\",\n      \"title\": \"Anti-spam protections on contact form (POSITIVE)\",\n      \"severity\": \"INFO\",\n      \"type\": \"POSITIVE_FINDING\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/components/ContactForm.tsx\",\n      \"lines\": [32, 33, 113, 117],\n      \"details\": \"The contact form implements multiple anti-spam measures: honeypot field (line 32, hidden 'company' input), human delay check (minimum 1500ms before submission allowed, line 113), and spam text pattern detection (line 117, checks for URLs, casino/crypto keywords, excessive @ symbols). These are applied via utilities in /repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/utils/antiSpam.ts.\",\n      \"data_types\": [],\n      \"recommendation\": \"No action needed. Consider adding CAPTCHA for additional protection.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-029\",\n      \"title\": \"Logger utility properly suppresses logs in production (POSITIVE but inconsistently used)\",\n      \"severity\": \"LOW\",\n      \"type\": \"INCONSISTENT_CONTROL\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/utils/logger.ts\",\n      \"details\": \"The logger utility only outputs logs when NODE_ENV === 'development'. However, many files use raw console.log/console.error instead of this utility. Files with raw console.log that runs in production include: src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx (11 calls), src/components/GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard.tsx (1 call), src/app/auth/google/callback/page.tsx (1 call), src/components/AddressSectionNew.tsx (2 calls), src/components/ProductInfo.tsx (1 call), src/app/[locale]/cart/page.tsx (1 call), src/lib/secureToken.ts (4 error calls). While most do not log actual secrets, some log token presence/absence status which could aid attackers in understanding the auth flow.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"debug_information\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"Replace all raw console.log/console.error calls with the logger utility to ensure no debug output in production.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"DS-030\",\n      \"title\": \"Input validation implemented for address/profile fields (POSITIVE)\",\n      \"severity\": \"INFO\",\n      \"type\": \"POSITIVE_FINDING\",\n      \"file\": \"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/utils/validation.ts\",\n      \"details\": \"The validation utility provides sanitization (sanitizeText strips HTML tags, control characters, and normalizes whitespace) and validation functions for phone, city, state, zip, country, and street fields. The PersonalInfo component (src/components/PersonalInfo.tsx line 10) imports and uses these. This reduces the risk of XSS or injection through profile fields.\",\n      \"data_types\": [\"address_data\", \"phone_number\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"No action needed. Ensure these validators are consistently applied to all user input paths.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}
