[2026-03-21 12:22:36] [pre-recon] [LLM] Turn 474: {"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RpEucTCN16Z4KZBMCTZ3M6","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/deliverables/code_analysis_deliverable.md","content":"# Penetration Test Scope & Boundaries — KamriHub Web (kamri-web)\n\n**Primary Directive:** This analysis is strictly limited to the **network-accessible attack surface** of the KamriHub e-commerce frontend application. All findings have been verified against the scope criteria below.\n\n### In-Scope: Network-Reachable Components\nA component is considered **in-scope** if its execution can be initiated, directly or indirectly, by a network request that the deployed application server is capable of receiving. This includes:\n- All 10 Next.js API route handlers under `/api/*`\n- All ~36 page routes under `/[locale]/*` served by the Next.js App Router\n- The built-in Next.js `/_next/image` image optimization endpoint\n- Edge middleware executing on every request (`src/middleware.ts`)\n- Google OAuth callback pages (`/auth/google/callback`, `/[locale]/auth/google/callback`)\n- Client-side JavaScript executing in the browser context of served pages\n\n### Out-of-Scope: Locally Executable Only\n- **Backend NestJS API (kamri-server):** Separate repository, not analyzed. Only client-side API call patterns are documented.\n- **Strapi CMS:** External service, not present in this codebase. Only API integration patterns are documented.\n- **Build tooling:** `next build`, ESLint, Vitest, Playwright — development/CI only.\n- **Monorepo packages:** `@kamri/lib` and `@kamri/ui` are internal build-time dependencies, not independently deployed services.\n- **Database migrations:** No database is directly managed by this frontend.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nThe KamriHub web application is a **Next.js 14 App Router** e-commerce frontend deployed on **Vercel**, communicating with a separate **NestJS backend API** on Railway. The application handles user authentication (OTP-based + Google OAuth), product browsing, shopping cart management, Stripe payment processing, and user profile management. The architecture creates a significant attack surface through several custom server-side proxy routes and overly permissive configurations.\n\n**The most critical security findings center around three interconnected weaknesses:** (1) Two custom image proxy API routes (`/api/avatar/[...path]` and `/api/strapi-image/[...path]`) accept arbitrary user-controlled path segments without validation, creating **full-read SSRF vulnerabilities** that can proxy responses from internal services back to the attacker. This is compounded by the Next.js image optimization endpoint (`/_next/image`) which is configured with wildcard hostname patterns (`hostname: '**'`) for both HTTP and HTTPS, effectively turning it into a universal server-side request proxy. (2) Authentication tokens (JWTs) are stored in `localStorage`, making them accessible to any XSS payload. The Content Security Policy includes `'unsafe-inline'` and `'unsafe-eval'` in `script-src`, effectively neutralizing browser-level XSS protection. A stored XSS vulnerability exists in product review rendering via `innerHTML` assignment of unsanitized third-party content. (3) The committed `.env` file contains a **Supabase service_role JWT** granting full administrative database access, and a hardcoded maintenance bypass code (`dev-bypass-2024`) exists as a fallback in the middleware source.\n\nThe combination of SSRF capabilities, weak CSP, XSS-accessible token storage, and exposed credentials creates a **high-risk attack chain**: an attacker could exploit SSRF to probe internal infrastructure, leverage XSS to steal authentication tokens, or combine the exposed Supabase service_role key with SSRF to achieve full database access. The absence of HSTS headers, server-side rate limiting (frontend-only localStorage-based rate limiter), and nonce-based CSP further reduces the defensive posture. Authentication relies entirely on client-side enforcement for route protection, with no server-side auth on any Next.js API route handler.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Architecture & Technology Stack\n\n### Framework & Language\n\nThe application is built with **Next.js 14.2.33** using the **App Router** architecture, **React 18**, and **TypeScript 5** with `strict: false` (reducing type safety). The frontend is styled with **Tailwind CSS 3** and uses **Zod** for schema validation in the shared library package. The project is structured as a monorepo with two internal packages: `@kamri/lib` (shared types, API client, Zod validation schemas) and `@kamri/ui` (shared React components). Security implications of this stack include: Next.js App Router provides both server-side rendering (RSC) and client-side hydration, meaning server components can make authenticated requests while client components handle user interaction. The `strict: false` TypeScript configuration weakens type checking, potentially allowing type-related bugs that could impact data validation. React 18's automatic JSX escaping provides baseline XSS protection for text content rendered via JSX expressions, but this does not protect against `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`, `innerHTML` assignments, or URL-context injections.\n\nNotable dependencies with security implications include: `multer` (v2.0.2) for file upload handling, `@stripe/stripe-js` and `@stripe/react-stripe-js` for client-side payment processing, and `zod` for input validation. **DOMPurify is referenced in code but is NOT installed as a dependency** — the sanitization utility falls back to a fragile regex-based approach. The `package-lock.json` exists for reproducible builds, but there is no automated dependency scanning (no Snyk, Dependabot, or similar tooling detected).\n\n### Architectural Pattern\n\nThis is a **client-heavy monolithic frontend** that delegates all business logic and data persistence to external services. The trust boundary architecture is:\n\n1. **Browser ↔ Vercel Edge**: Edge middleware handles CSP headers, locale routing, and maintenance mode bypass. The middleware matcher explicitly **excludes** `/api` paths, meaning API routes receive NO middleware security headers.\n2. **Vercel ↔ Railway Backend**: JWT Bearer tokens authenticate requests from the frontend to the backend API at `kamri-server-production.up.railway.app`. All business logic validation occurs server-side.\n3. **Next.js API Routes as Proxies**: The `/api/avatar/[...path]` and `/api/strapi-image/[...path]` routes act as server-side proxies, creating SSRF attack surfaces. These routes make outbound requests based on user-controlled path segments.\n4. **External Services**: Supabase (avatar storage), Strapi CMS (campaigns/content), Stripe (payments), Google OAuth (SSO), Google Maps (address autocomplete), CJDropshipping (product fulfillment/reviews).\n\n### Critical Security Components\n\nThe security-critical infrastructure includes: (1) **Edge middleware** (`src/middleware.ts`) — applies CSP, security headers, locale routing, and maintenance mode with a bypass mechanism; (2) **Token management** (`src/lib/secureToken.ts`) — dual-layer JWT storage in memory + localStorage; (3) **Auth context** (`src/contexts/AuthContext.tsx`) — manages authentication state, session expiration, and cross-tab synchronization; (4) **API client** (`src/lib/api.ts`) — central HTTP client for all backend communication with Bearer token injection; (5) **Safe redirect utility** (`src/lib/security/safeRedirect.ts`) — open redirect prevention; (6) **Input validation** (`src/utils/validation.ts`, `src/utils/sanitize.ts`, `src/utils/antiSpam.ts`) — text sanitization, HTML escaping, and anti-spam measures.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Authentication & Authorization Deep Dive\n\n### Authentication Mechanisms and Endpoints\n\nThe application uses a **passwordless OTP (One-Time Password)** system as the primary authentication flow, with **Google OAuth** as an SSO alternative. Legacy password-based login/registration endpoints still exist in the API client but appear unused in the primary UI flow. All authentication API calls originate from the `ApiClient` class at `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/api.ts`.\n\n**Complete list of authentication API endpoints called by the frontend:**\n\n| Endpoint | Method | File | Line | Auth Required | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| `/api/auth/login` | POST | `src/lib/api.ts` | 184-208 | No | Legacy email/password login (password sent as empty string in practice) |\n| `/api/auth/request-otp` | POST | `src/lib/api.ts` | 211-233 | No | Request OTP code via email |\n| `/api/auth/verify-otp` | POST | `src/lib/api.ts` | 235-268 | No | Verify OTP code, returns JWT |\n| `/api/auth/register` | POST | `src/lib/api.ts` | 270-294 | No | User registration (sends `role: 'user'` — client-controllable!) |\n| `/auth/google` | Redirect | `src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` | 176 | No | Initiate Google OAuth (backend handles) |\n| `/auth/google/callback` | GET | `src/app/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` | 1-31 | No | Google OAuth callback (no-locale redirect) |\n| `/[locale]/auth/google/callback` | GET | `src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` | 1-314 | No | Google OAuth callback (token extraction) |\n| `/api/users/profile` | GET | `src/lib/api.ts` | 303-338 | Yes | Fetch user profile |\n| `/api/users/profile` | PUT | `src/lib/api.ts` | 340-370 | Yes | Update user profile |\n| `/api/users/profile/avatar` | POST | `src/lib/api.ts` | 1532-1549 | Yes | Upload avatar (FormData) |\n| `/api/user-settings/account` | DELETE | `src/lib/api.ts` | 1233-1237 | Yes | Delete user account |\n\n**Security concerns with authentication endpoints:**\n- **Registration sends client-controlled `role: 'user'`** (line 277 of `api.ts`): If the backend does not explicitly ignore this field, an attacker could register with `role: 'admin'` for privilege escalation.\n- **Logout is client-side only** (lines 296-300 of `api.ts`): The token is cleared from memory and localStorage, but NO server-side call invalidates it. Stolen tokens remain valid until expiration.\n- **OTP has 10-second client-side timeout** but rate limiting is localStorage-based and trivially bypassable.\n\n### Session Management and Token Security\n\n**Token Storage:** JWTs are stored in a dual-layer system at `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/lib/secureToken.ts`:\n- **In-memory variable** (`memoryToken`, line 20) — primary reference\n- **localStorage** (`auth_token` key, line 34) — persistence across page reloads\n\nThe \"memory-first\" approach provides **no additional XSS protection** because the token is always written to localStorage (line 34). Any XSS payload can execute `localStorage.getItem('auth_token')` to exfiltrate the JWT. The code comments (line 19) claiming enhanced security are misleading.\n\n**Session cookie flags — exact locations:**\n\n| Cookie | File | Line | HttpOnly | Secure | SameSite | MaxAge |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| `maintenance_bypass` | `src/middleware.ts` | 137-142 | ✅ (line 138) | ✅ prod only (line 139) | `lax` (line 140) | 7 days (line 141) |\n| `NEXT_LOCALE` (server) | `src/middleware.ts` | 187 | ❌ Missing | ❌ Missing | ❌ Missing | 1 year |\n| `language` (client) | `src/contexts/LanguageContext.tsx` | 91 | ❌ Missing | ❌ Missing | ❌ Missing | Session |\n| `NEXT_LOCALE` (client) | `src/contexts/LanguageContext.tsx` | 93, 158 | ❌ Missing | ❌ Missing | ❌ Missing | 1 year |\n\n**Note:** The auth token itself is **NOT stored in a cookie** — it is in localStorage, making it immune to CSRF but vulnerable to XSS.\n\n**Session Duration:** 24-hour maximum enforced client-side (`SESSION_MAX_DURATION` at `AuthContext.tsx` line 14). A periodic check runs every 60 seconds (line 182). The client-side JWT expiration check (`src/lib/security/jwt.ts` lines 5-12) treats tokens with no `exp` claim as **never expiring** (line 10: `if (typeof payload.exp !== 'number') return false`).\n\n### Authorization Model\n\n**There is NO frontend-side authorization enforcement.** The admin layout (`src/app/[locale]/admin/layout.tsx`, lines 15-17) only sets `noindex/nofollow` metadata — no auth check. The admin page (`src/app/[locale]/admin/page.tsx`) is a placeholder with no access control. Profile, checkout, and order pages rely entirely on client-side `useAuth()` context checks that can be bypassed by disabling JavaScript or making direct API requests. All real authorization is expected to be enforced by the backend API via the Bearer token.\n\nThe `User` type includes an optional `role?: string` field (`AuthContext.tsx` line 24) but this field is never checked in any conditional logic in the frontend.\n\n### SSO/OAuth/OIDC Flows\n\n**Google OAuth Flow:**\n1. Frontend redirects to `{API_BASE_URL}/auth/google` (backend handles OAuth with Google)\n2. Backend validates the Google response and generates a JWT\n3. Backend redirects to `/auth/google/callback?token=JWT_TOKEN`\n4. Frontend extracts the token from URL query string or hash fragment\n\n**State parameter validation:** The backend handles `state` generation and validation. The frontend callback page handles a `reason: 'state'` error code at line 40 of `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx`, confirming backend validation exists.\n\n**Nonce parameter:** There is **NO evidence of nonce generation or validation** anywhere in the frontend codebase.\n\n**Token transport via URL (CRITICAL):** The JWT is passed from backend to frontend via URL query parameter (`?token=...`) at `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` lines 16-37. This exposes the token in:\n- Browser history\n- Web server access logs\n- Referrer headers sent to third-party resources\n- Analytics platforms\n- Proxy logs\n\nWhile `history.replaceState` is called later (line 124) to clean the URL, there is a window where the token is visible.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Data Security & Storage\n\n### Database Security\n\nThis frontend application does **not directly access any database**. All data operations are delegated to the backend NestJS API via REST calls. However, the committed `.env` file contains a **Supabase service_role JWT** (`SUPABASE_KEY` at `.env` line 15) for project `fzcgqswwhvukwrawfhev.supabase.co`. This key grants full admin access: bypasses Row Level Security (RLS), can read/write/delete any data, manage auth users, and access storage. The JWT payload shows `\"role\":\"service_role\"` with expiration in 2035. While `.env` is in `.gitignore`, its presence in the working directory means any developer with repo access has this key.\n\nThe Supabase integration in the frontend is limited to avatar storage (uploading user profile images). The frontend uses a `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_DEFAULT_KEY` for client-side operations, but the service_role key appears to be used server-side (in the avatar proxy route context). There is a notable **mismatch between two Supabase project URLs**: the publishable key points to `ayeiqxvlzetfpipjzjta.supabase.co` while the service_role key points to `fzcgqswwhvukwrawfhev.supabase.co`, suggesting either a migration in progress or misconfiguration.\n\n### Data Flow Security\n\n**Sensitive data flows identified:**\n\n1. **Authentication tokens:** Created by backend → transmitted via URL (OAuth) or response body (OTP) → stored in localStorage → sent as Bearer header on authenticated requests. XSS-accessible throughout the lifecycle.\n\n2. **Payment data:** Handled correctly via Stripe Elements. Card data never touches the application server. Payment intents are created server-side via `apiClient.createPaymentIntent()` (`src/components/checkout/PaymentStep.tsx` line 124). The `clientSecret` is passed to Stripe.js for confirmation. `SavedCard` objects contain only `brand`, `last4`, `expMonth`, `expYear` — never full card numbers.\n\n3. **PII in forms:** Contact form data (name, email, phone, subject, message, orderNumber) is **auto-saved to localStorage** every 2 seconds as a draft (`src/components/ContactForm.tsx` lines 48, 62-69) with no TTL. On shared computers, this PII persists indefinitely for the next user.\n\n4. **Google OAuth callback** logs user PII (userId, email) to browser console in production (`src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` line 200) using raw `console.log` instead of the dev-only logger utility.\n\n5. **Order confirmation** reads `orderId` from URL parameters (`src/app/[locale]/order-confirmation/page.tsx` line 37). If the backend doesn't enforce ownership validation, order IDs could be enumerated to access other users' order details.\n\n### Environment Variable Exposure\n\n**Browser-exposed variables (NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix):**\n- `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` — Backend API base URL\n- `NEXT_PUBLIC_STRAPI_URL` — Strapi CMS URL\n- `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` — Supabase project URL\n- `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_DEFAULT_KEY` — Supabase anon key\n- `NEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY` — Stripe publishable key (test: `pk_test_51SU1sP...`)\n- `NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY` — Google Maps API key (`AIzaSyCtl...`)\n\n**Server-only secrets in `.env`:**\n- `SUPABASE_KEY` — Supabase service_role JWT (HIGH risk if exposed)\n- `STRAPI_LICENSE` — Base64-encoded Strapi license\n- `MAINTENANCE_BYPASS_CODE` — Maintenance bypass code (defaults to `dev-bypass-2024`)\n\n### Multi-tenant Data Isolation\n\nThere is **no multi-tenancy** in this application. It is a single-tenant e-commerce frontend. User data isolation depends entirely on the backend API's authorization enforcement. The frontend passes the user's JWT on authenticated requests, and the backend is expected to scope data access to the authenticated user.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}
