[2026-03-21 12:25:39] [pre-recon] [LLM] Turn 478: {"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HFuQ9Q1eLUYG4WNNjyKUrB","name":"Edit","input":{"replace_all":false,"file_path":"/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web/deliverables/code_analysis_deliverable.md","old_string":"- **No structured logging, error tracking (Sentry/Datadog), or security event monitoring** detected.\n- **next.config.js** removes all `console.*` except `console.error` in production builds (lines 13-16), BUT this only applies to client-side code bundled by webpack. Server-side console calls in API routes may still execute.","new_string":"- **No structured logging, error tracking (Sentry/Datadog), or security event monitoring** detected.\n- **next.config.js** removes all `console.*` except `console.error` in production builds (lines 13-16), BUT this only applies to client-side code bundled by webpack. Server-side console calls in API routes may still execute.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Overall Codebase Indexing\n\nThe KamriHub web codebase is a **Next.js 14 App Router monorepo** rooted at `/repos/KamriHub/kamri-web`. The primary application source resides in `src/`, which follows the standard Next.js App Router convention: `src/app/` contains all route definitions (pages and API handlers), `src/components/` houses React components, `src/contexts/` contains React context providers (including the critical `AuthContext.tsx`), `src/lib/` holds utility libraries and API clients, `src/utils/` contains helper functions, `src/constants/` stores application constants, and `src/types/` defines TypeScript interfaces. The `src/app/` directory uses locale-based routing (`[locale]/`) as the top-level dynamic segment, with nested directories for each page feature (auth, profile, checkout, cart, product, admin, etc.). API routes are under `src/app/api/` and use the Next.js Route Handler convention with `route.ts` files. The monorepo includes two internal packages at `packages/lib/` (`@kamri/lib` — shared types, Zod schemas, API type definitions) and `packages/ui/` (`@kamri/ui` — shared React components).\n\nSecurity-relevant code is distributed across several directories without a centralized security module: authentication logic spans `src/lib/api.ts` (API calls), `src/lib/secureToken.ts` (token storage), `src/lib/security/jwt.ts` (JWT parsing), `src/lib/security/safeRedirect.ts` (redirect validation), `src/contexts/AuthContext.tsx` (state management), and `src/components/AuthModal.tsx` (UI + honeypot). Security middleware is in `src/middleware.ts` at the root of `src/`. Input validation is split between `src/utils/validation.ts`, `src/utils/sanitize.ts`, and `src/utils/antiSpam.ts`. The SSRF-vulnerable proxy routes are in `src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts` and `src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts`. Configuration files at the root include `next.config.js`, `vercel.json`, `tsconfig.json`, `package.json`, `.env`, and `.env.local`. This distributed layout means a security auditor must examine files across at least 8 different directories to achieve comprehensive coverage. There is no `security/` or `auth/` top-level directory — security logic is discovered only by understanding the full component graph.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Critical File Paths\n\n### Configuration\n- `src/middleware.ts` — Edge middleware: CSP, security headers, maintenance bypass, locale routing\n- `next.config.js` — Next.js config: CSP headers, image remote patterns (wildcard!), console removal\n- `vercel.json` — Vercel deployment config: security headers, CORS on /api/*\n- `tsconfig.json` — TypeScript config (`strict: false`)\n- `.env` — Environment variables (contains Supabase service_role key, Stripe key, maintenance bypass code)\n- `.env.local` — Local env overrides (contains Google Maps API key)\n- `.gitignore` — Git ignore rules (excludes .env files)\n- `package.json` — Dependency manifest with version ranges\n\n### Authentication & Authorization\n- `src/lib/api.ts` — API client with ALL auth endpoints (login, OTP, register, profile, logout)\n- `src/lib/secureToken.ts` — Auth token storage (memory + localStorage), token lifecycle\n- `src/lib/authToken.ts` — Deprecated wrapper, re-exports from secureToken.ts\n- `src/lib/security/jwt.ts` — Client-side JWT expiration check (no signature verification)\n- `src/lib/security/safeRedirect.ts` — Open redirect prevention utility\n- `src/contexts/AuthContext.tsx` — Auth state management, session expiration, cross-tab sync\n- `src/components/AuthModal.tsx` — Login/OTP UI, honeypot anti-spam, Google OAuth redirect\n- `src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` — Google OAuth callback (token extraction from URL, PII logging)\n- `src/app/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` — Google OAuth redirect (no-locale version)\n- `src/components/GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard.tsx` — Detects stale OAuth params, redirects\n- `src/types/authContext.ts` — Auth context type definitions\n- `src/constants/security.ts` — Security messaging constants\n\n### API & Routing\n- `src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts` — Avatar image proxy (SSRF vulnerability)\n- `src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts` — Strapi image proxy (SSRF vulnerability)\n- `src/app/api/stripe/config/route.ts` — Stripe publishable key endpoint\n- `src/app/api/analyze-product/route.ts` — Product analysis debug endpoint (no auth)\n- `src/lib/server-api.ts` — Server-side API client (hardcoded backend URL fallback)\n- `src/lib/strapi.ts` — Strapi CMS API integration\n- `src/lib/api-base-url.ts` — API base URL normalization\n\n### Data Models & DB Interaction\n- `src/lib/api.ts` — Contains all API call patterns to backend (user, orders, products, cart, etc.)\n- `src/app/[locale]/order-confirmation/page.tsx` — Order lookup via URL parameter\n- `src/app/[locale]/cart/page.tsx` — Cart/checkout data flow, sessionStorage usage\n- `src/components/checkout/PaymentStep.tsx` — Stripe payment intent handling\n\n### Dependency Manifests\n- `package.json` — Main application dependencies\n- `package-lock.json` — Locked dependency versions\n- `packages/lib/package.json` — Shared library package\n- `packages/ui/package.json` — Shared UI package\n\n### Sensitive Data & Secrets Handling\n- `.env` — Supabase service_role JWT, Stripe key, maintenance bypass code, Strapi license\n- `.env.local` — Google Maps API key\n- `src/lib/secureToken.ts` — JWT storage in localStorage\n- `src/lib/cookieConsent.ts` — GDPR cookie consent management (localStorage-based)\n- `src/components/ContactForm.tsx` — PII auto-saved to localStorage drafts\n\n### Middleware & Input Validation\n- `src/middleware.ts` — Main security middleware (CSP, headers, maintenance bypass)\n- `src/utils/sanitize.ts` — HTML sanitization (DOMPurify fallback, regex backup)\n- `src/utils/validation.ts` — Text/address input validation\n- `src/utils/antiSpam.ts` — Anti-spam: honeypot, timing, email validation\n- `src/lib/rateLimiter.ts` — Client-side rate limiting (localStorage-based, bypassable)\n\n### Logging & Monitoring\n- `src/utils/logger.ts` — Dev-only logger utility (inconsistently used)\n- `src/app/[locale]/auth/google/callback/page.tsx` — Production console.log with PII (line 200)\n\n### Infrastructure & Deployment\n- `vercel.json` — Vercel deployment config, CORS, security headers\n- `next.config.js` — Next.js build config, image optimization, CSP\n- `src/middleware.ts` — Edge middleware (Vercel Edge Functions)\n\n### XSS-Relevant Files\n- `src/components/ProductReviews.tsx` — innerHTML assignment with third-party review data (line 13)\n- `src/components/ProductReviewsModal.tsx` — innerHTML assignment with third-party review data (line 12)\n- `src/components/CategoryItemListJsonLd.tsx` — dangerouslySetInnerHTML with JSON-LD (line 35)\n- `src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/ProductJsonLd.tsx` — dangerouslySetInnerHTML with JSON-LD (line 81)\n- `src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/BreadcrumbJsonLd.tsx` — dangerouslySetInnerHTML with JSON-LD (line 48)\n- `src/app/layout-scripts.tsx` — dangerouslySetInnerHTML for consent mode script (line 33)\n\n### SSRF-Relevant Files\n- `src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts` — Full-read SSRF proxy (lines 15, 36, 55)\n- `src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts` — Multi-vector SSRF proxy (lines 37, 65, 89, 123, 152, 167)\n- `next.config.js` — Wildcard image optimization config (lines 18-29)\n\n### User-Facing Components with Security Relevance\n- `src/components/AccountSettings.tsx` — Non-functional account deletion (GDPR concern)\n- `src/components/AccountSettingsNew.tsx` — Working account deletion (line 322)\n- `src/components/PersonalInfo.tsx` — Profile form with validation\n- `src/components/AddressSectionNew.tsx` — Address input with Google Maps\n- `src/app/[locale]/admin/layout.tsx` — Admin layout (no auth guard, lines 15-17)\n- `src/app/[locale]/admin/page.tsx` — Admin page (no access control)\n- `src/app/[locale]/profile/layout.tsx` — Profile layout (no server-side auth guard)\n- `src/app/[locale]/checkout/layout.tsx` — Checkout layout (no server-side auth guard)\n- `src/app/[locale]/search/page.tsx` — Search with reflected query parameter (lines 141, 212)\n\n---\n\n## 9. XSS Sinks and Render Contexts\n\n### Critical XSS Findings\n\n**FINDING XSS-001: Stored XSS via innerHTML in Product Reviews [CRITICAL]**\n\nTwo components render third-party product review data using `innerHTML` without sanitization:\n\n- **File:** `src/components/ProductReviews.tsx`, line 13\n- **File:** `src/components/ProductReviewsModal.tsx`, line 12\n\nBoth files contain a `decodeHtmlEntities()` function that creates a textarea element and assigns user-supplied review comment text to `textArea.innerHTML`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction decodeHtmlEntities(text: string): string {\n  const textArea = document.createElement('textarea');\n  textArea.innerHTML = text; // SINK: innerHTML assignment with unsanitized data\n  return textArea.value;\n}\n```\n\n**Data flow:** Review comments originate from the CJDropshipping product reviews API — this is user-generated content from third-party buyers. The data flows through: CJDropshipping API → backend API → frontend `api.ts` fetch → React state → `decodeHtmlEntities()` → `innerHTML`.\n\n**Render context:** HTML Body Context. The `innerHTML` assignment parses HTML including event handlers during assignment, before `.value` is read. A malicious review containing `<img src=x onerror=alert(document.cookie)>` would trigger script execution.\n\n**Risk:** HIGH — Combined with `localStorage` token storage and CSP `unsafe-inline`, this enables full account takeover via stolen JWT.\n\n---\n\n**FINDING XSS-002: DOMPurify Not Installed — Sanitizer is Non-Functional [HIGH]**\n\n- **File:** `src/utils/sanitize.ts`\n\nThe `sanitizeHtml()` function references `window.DOMPurify` (lines 36-41, 64-68) but DOMPurify is **not in `package.json` dependencies**. The DOMPurify code path never executes. The regex fallback in production mode (lines 71-77) escapes all HTML. In development mode (lines 44-58), the regex-based approach strips tags then re-enables specific tags — this is fragile and bypassable.\n\n**Critical observation:** `sanitizeHtml()` is **never called anywhere in the codebase** — including the product review components where it's most needed. The utility exists but is unused.\n\n---\n\n**FINDING XSS-003: JSON-LD Script Breakout via `</script>` [MEDIUM]**\n\nThree components use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with `JSON.stringify()` for JSON-LD structured data, where product/category names come from the API:\n\n- **File:** `src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/ProductJsonLd.tsx`, line 81\n  - **Sink:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}`\n  - **Context:** Inside `<script type=\"application/ld+json\">`\n  - **Data source:** Product name, description from backend API\n\n- **File:** `src/app/[locale]/product/[slug]/BreadcrumbJsonLd.tsx`, line 48\n  - **Sink:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}`\n  - **Context:** Inside `<script type=\"application/ld+json\">`\n  - **Data source:** Product/category names from backend API\n\n- **File:** `src/components/CategoryItemListJsonLd.tsx`, line 35\n  - **Sink:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(jsonLd) }}`\n  - **Context:** Inside `<script type=\"application/ld+json\">`\n  - **Data source:** Category names from backend API\n\n`JSON.stringify()` does NOT escape `</script>` sequences. If a product name contains `</script><script>alert(1)</script>`, it would break out of the JSON-LD script context. Requires backend or CJDropshipping API data compromise to exploit.\n\n---\n\n**FINDING XSS-004: Open Redirect via GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard [MEDIUM]**\n\n- **File:** `src/components/GoogleCallbackRedirectGuard.tsx`, line 31\n- **Sink:** `window.location.replace(cleanUrl)`\n- **Context:** URL context\n- **Data source:** `window.location.search` and `window.location.hash` passed verbatim\n\nWhile the base path is fixed to the current path, the query parameters and hash fragment from the current URL are preserved in the redirect target. This is a limited open redirect / parameter injection vector.\n\n---\n\n**FINDING XSS-005: Reflected Search Query in JSX [LOW]**\n\n- **File:** `src/app/[locale]/search/page.tsx`, lines 141, 212\n- **Sink:** JSX text node rendering of URL parameter `q`\n- **Context:** HTML body (React JSX)\n- **Data source:** URL query parameter `?q=...`\n\nReact's automatic JSX escaping prevents XSS here, but the search query from the URL is reflected on the page. Risk is LOW due to React's built-in escaping.\n\n---\n\n### Non-Vulnerable Sinks (Analyzed and Cleared)\n\n- **`src/app/layout-scripts.tsx` line 33:** `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with static Google Consent Mode script — no user input. **Safe.**\n- **`eval()`, `Function()`, `setTimeout(string)`, `setInterval(string)`:** NONE found in the codebase. **No JavaScript context XSS sinks.**\n- **jQuery sinks:** NONE — no jQuery dependency. **No jQuery-based XSS.**\n- **SQL injection:** NONE — frontend only, no database access. **Not applicable.**\n- **Command injection:** NONE — no `exec`, `spawn`, or `child_process` usage. **Not applicable.**\n- **Template injection:** NONE — no server-side template engines. **Not applicable.**\n- **Deserialization:** `JSON.parse` is used for standard API response processing. No unsafe deserialization patterns found.\n\n---\n\n## 10. SSRF Sinks\n\n### Critical SSRF Findings\n\n**FINDING SSRF-001: Avatar Proxy — Full-Read SSRF via Backend Fallback [CRITICAL]**\n\n- **File:** `src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts`, lines 49-92\n- **Entry Point:** `GET /api/avatar/[...path]`\n- **Sink:** `fetch(imageUrl, { redirect: 'follow' })` at line 55\n\nWhen Supabase is not configured or all Supabase candidates fail, the proxy falls back to fetching from the backend server:\n\n```typescript\nconst serverUrl = apiUrl.replace(/\\/api$/, '');\nconst imageUrl = `${serverUrl}/uploads/users/${imagePath}`;\nconst response = await fetch(imageUrl, {\n  redirect: 'follow', // Follows redirects to ANY destination\n});\nconst imageBuffer = await response.arrayBuffer();\nreturn new NextResponse(imageBuffer, { ... }); // Full response proxied back\n```\n\n**User-controlled input:** The `imagePath` is constructed from the catch-all `[...path]` URL segments joined with `/` (line 15: `const imagePath = path.join('/')`). There is **zero validation** — no allowlist, no path traversal check, no character restriction.\n\n**Attack vectors:**\n- `GET /api/avatar/..%2F..%2Fapi%2Fusers%2Fprofile` → Fetches and proxies `backend-server/api/users/profile`\n- Path traversal via `../` escapes the `/uploads/users/` prefix\n- `redirect: 'follow'` means a backend redirect to an internal service URL would be followed\n\n**Notable bug:** Code comment (line 59) says \"Ne pas suivre les redirections\" (Do not follow redirects) but code does `redirect: 'follow'` — the opposite.\n\n**Impact:** Full response body from any URL reachable from the Vercel serverless function is proxied back to the attacker. CORS headers set to `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` (line 89).\n\n---\n\n**FINDING SSRF-002: Avatar Proxy — SSRF via Supabase Branch [HIGH]**\n\n- **File:** `src/app/api/avatar/[...path]/route.ts`, lines 13-46\n- **Entry Point:** `GET /api/avatar/[...path]`\n- **Sink:** `fetch(url, { method: 'HEAD' })` at line 36\n\nWhen `SUPABASE_PUBLIC_URL` is configured, four candidate URLs are constructed:\n\n```typescript\nconst candidates = [\n  `${supabasePublic}/uploads/users/${imagePath}`,\n  `${supabasePublic}/images/${imagePath}`,\n  `${supabasePublic}/users/${imagePath}`,\n  `${supabasePublic}/${imagePath}`,  // Full path control on Supabase host\n];\n```\n\nThe last candidate gives full path control on the Supabase host. HEAD requests are made to each. If any returns 200, a **307 redirect** is sent to the client. Path traversal can reach Supabase REST API or Auth API endpoints.\n\n**Attack:** `GET /api/avatar/../../../rest/v1/users?select=*` → HEAD request to `https://supabase-host/rest/v1/users?select=*`\n\n---\n\n**FINDING SSRF-003: Strapi Image Proxy — Multi-Vector SSRF [CRITICAL]**\n\n- **File:** `src/app/api/strapi-image/[...path]/route.ts`, lines 13-235\n- **Entry Point:** `GET /api/strapi-image/[...path]?id=OPTIONAL`\n\nThis proxy has **three distinct SSRF attack vectors:**\n\n**Vector 1 — Direct Path Control (lines 117-128):**\n```typescript\nconst imageUrl = `${baseUrl}${imagePath.startsWith('/') ? imagePath : `/${imagePath}`}`;\nresponse = await fetch(imageUrl, { redirect: 'follow' });\n```\nUser-controlled path segments directly appended to Strapi base URL. Path traversal reaches arbitrary Strapi endpoints.\n\n**Vector 2 — Indirect SSRF via Strapi API Response (lines 33-101):**\nWhen `?id=` is provided, the proxy queries `${baseUrl}/api/upload/files/${fileId}`, then fetches the `url` field from the JSON response:\n```typescript\nconst finalUrl = fileUrl.startsWith('http')\n  ? fileUrl                    // Absolute URL from Strapi DB — NO validation\n  :